<HEADLINE> EU, NATO to Meet Next Week on European Defense Capability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
NATO will hold their first formal meeting next Tuesday to discuss
how to enhance European defense capability, a senior NATO official
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It is believed the meeting between NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana and the EU rotating president, Austrian Foreign
Minister Wolfgang Schussel, will focus on measures designed to
enhance European Security and Defense Identity (ESDI) within NATO.
</P>
<P>
The ESDI concept would supposedly provide NATO assets to
European member states to form a European defense organization to
deal with security issues without the participation of the United
States or other non-European member states.
</P>
<P>
NATO has already formed and developed a multinational Combined
Joint Task Force that is reported to be one of the available NATO
assets for ESDI operations.
</P>
<P>
The NATO European members brought up the ESDI issue again after
the Kosovo crisis flared up. The EU foreign and defense ministers
met in September and October to discuss the issue but did not
accomplish much.
</P>
<P>
As a run-up to next Tuesday's EU-NATO meeting, an agreement was
struck between Britain and France that the European Union must
have the capacity to respond to global crises while respecting
their obligations to NATO.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after a summit between the two
countries at Saint-Malo. A joint statement following the summit
said the EU should be capable of autonomous action "backed up by
credible military force."
</P>
<P>
France is a country that has long championed the concept of
ESDI, while Britain is one that has so far opted more for NATO
solidarity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
