<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Progress as NBA Players, Owners Meet for 10 Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- NBA Commissioner David
Stern publicly acknowledged the possibility of canceling the
entire season after NBA owners and the Players Association met
for more than 10 hours Thursday but reported little progress.
</P>
<P>
With the lockout in its 157th day, owners rejected a union
offer to send the talks to mediation and Stern sounded ominous
when referring to a NBPA call to set an "ratificial deadline" for
saving the season.
</P>
<P>
"That's something I find sufficiently abhorrent," Stern said
late Thursday night. "Our view is that the season will expire of
its own weight, whenever that time is. There's nothing that I'm
planning to do to push that ahead to an artificial limitation.
</P>
<P>
"But I now recognize the possibility, if not the likelihood,
that the season will expire and that the $1.1 billion in
guaranteed salary that would have been available and the
attendant revenues for the owners is now severely at risk."
</P>
<P>
No new talks are scheduled but time continues to run out. A
total of 225 games already have been lost to the lockout through
Friday and with a month needed to sign players and hold training
camps, an additional 200 will be canceled before even an
abbreviated season can begin.
</P>
<P>
No new proposals were submitted during the lengthy bargaining
session Thursday and NBPA executive director Billy Hunter
suggested the talks may have taken a step backwards when owners
shifted their support back to a hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care if we spend 15 hours or 20 hours in a room, we'
re not going to get worn down, we're not going to enter into any
bad deal because of attrition," Hunter said at a news conference
well after midnight. We've come too far, we've been locked out
too many days, our players have suffered as a group too much for
us to give it all up now, at the 12th hour."
</P>
<P>
Thursday's session began on an optimistic note with the
return of superstar Michael Jordan, who had not attended the
talks since October 28. He left early Thursday night but returned
several hours later.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the owners and players met face-to-face
for the first time since November 20. But there was no hint of
optimism, not even after more than 10 hours of discussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
