<HEADLINE> World Court Declines Jurisdiction Over Fisheries Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Court of
Justice Friday decided it does not have jurisdiction over Spain's
petition against Canada concerning the seizing of a Spanish
fishing vessel, according to Canada's Justice department.
</P>
<P>
On March 9, 1995, the Spanish fishing vessel "Estai" was seized
and its owner arrested by Canadian officials in the Northwest
Atlantic Fisheries Organization (NAFO) Regulatory Area for
violations of the Coastal Fisheries Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
Spain then filed a petition against Canada at the International
Court of Justice, claiming the Court had jurisdiction over the
case since Canada had agreed on a general acceptance of the
Court's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The Court however held that it could not hear the petition
because the dispute falls within the terms of Canada's reservation
to its general acceptance of the Court's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
Every country has the right to make a "reservation" about which
matters the Court will not have jurisdiction to hear, the Court
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Canadian Justice Minister Anne Mclellan welcomed the
Court's decision, saying it affirms the importance of the consent
of states to the jurisdiction of the International Court of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
"The International Court of Justice is one excellent tool to
resolve disputes between States, but we prefer it when we can
negotiate a good settlement, as we have already done on the
Northwest Atlantic fishery with the European Union," said Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
