<HEADLINE> EU Proposes TAC, Quotas For 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
adopted the 1999 proposal on total allowable catches (TACs) for a
group of fish stocks and their allocation under national quotas.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body, the European Commission, said here
Friday that these proposals are based on the most recent
scientific advice.
</P>
<P>
The advice came from the International Council for the
Exploration of the Sea which is composed of the EU member states
as well as all the North Atlantic coastal states, including the
United States, Canada, Norway and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The advice stressed the need for taking urgent measures to
protect fish stocks, which are facing an immediate biological
threat.
</P>
<P>
The European commission pointed out that the current state of
fish stocks shows a situation where concerns remain for a number
of stocks that are essential to European fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The EU had to avoid making drastic TAC cuts on the sector
unless they were absolutely necessary, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the EU said, scientific recommendations leading to
substantial cuts have only been adopted where there was a risk of
stock collapse.
</P>
<P>
Other proposals for cuts had to consider the fact that actual
catches have systematically been lower than the TACs, and that TAC
cuts will not result in new constraints, referring to the case for
North Sea whitings and Southern langoustine, according to the
commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
