<HEADLINE> Russia's GDP to Continue to Drop Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Russia's economy might contract
by 5 percent to 7 percent next year if the country does not get
more aid from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Russia's
Ministry of Economy said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted First Deputy Minister of
Economics Arkady Samokhvalov as saying that the forecast was made
by taking into account the "less favorable" factors: negative
results of talks to restructure the country's foreign debts,
delays in receiving foreign loans, and a continuing drop in world
market commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
Under this scenario, issuing new money could be up to 130
billion rubles (about seven billion U.S. dollars) and the annual
inflation rate could be as high as 50-60 percent. The ruble is
also expected to devaluate sharply.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of the jobless could rise to 9.3 million,
or 12.7 percent of the workforce, and the subsistence level could
go up by 20-40 percent by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under a more optimistic scenario, all matters relating to
foreign loans and debt restructuring may be settled quickly, and
the government's anti-crisis measures could produce more positive
results.
</P>
<P>
In this case, Russia's GDP could drop no more than 3 percent,
and the inflation rate would be around 30 percent next year, with
the unemployment number remaining at about 2.4 million, or 3.3
percent of the workforce in 1999, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
