<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Reporters Urged to Be Patriotic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean minister Friday
urged local journalists to be more patriotic.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Information, Posts and Telecommunications Chen
Chimutengwende made the remarks at Zimpapers Company long service
awards ceremony here in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, "the media of any country have the
obligation to report and criticize, not in the interests of
foreign values and agendas, but in the interest of enhancing
national development, national unity and national identity."
</P>
<P>
He said it was a disgrace to the profession and the nation
that Zimbabwean journalists who wrote for foreign publications
churned out reports that damaged the country's image.
</P>
<P>
"A sense of national belonging and national interest should be
the overriding characteristic in all our reports," Chimutengwende
noted.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has suffered bad publicity especially abroad where
the deteriorating economic environment, the land redistribution
program, anti-gay laws and a restless labor movement have made
headlines, he complained.
</P>
<P>
Of the 85 workers who received long service awards for working
for the company for 15 to 40 years, three were women.
</P>
<P>
The minister commended the company for its good management
which has seen it survive in economic hardships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
