<HEADLINE> Russia to Honor Missile Contract With Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian ambassador to Cyprus
Georgi Mouradov said Friday that his government would honor the
missile contract it has signed with the Cyprus government.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements by the U.S. ambassador Kenneth Brill,
that the missiles should not come to Cyprus, Mouradov said "Russia
and Cyprus are two sovereign states that discuss matters of mutual
interest. We consider the contract as a bilateral contract and we
will fulfill the terms of our contract".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
anti-aircraft missiles in a bid to booster its defense.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other western countries have criticized Cyprus for
the deal, and Turkey has threatened to launch preemptive military
strikes if the missiles are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there is a timetable for the implementation of the
contract, Mouradov said "when, where and how the contract will be
put into effect is a matter that concerns the defense of the
Republic of Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
"We are not violating international law through our contract
and through the cooperation we have in the military and
technological fields," Mouradov said.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia and Cyprus would be pleased to hear any American
initiative on demilitarization or the reduction of arms in Cyprus.
But he noted that "as far as the contract is concerned Russia and
Cyprus will deal with that".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in 1974
following a failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
