<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Bans Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's presidential powers
regulations effecting the ban on stay-aways and spelling
penalties for both employees and employers were made known here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government gazette said that any collective action for the
purpose of resisting a lawful measure or compelling the
government to alter any law is now outlawed, the Zimbabwe News
Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
Unlawful collective action covers strikes, boycott, lock-out,
sit-in, sit-out, stay-away or any concerted action by employers
or employees.
</P>
<P>
Under the new measures, Minister of Public Service, Labor and
Social Welfare Florence Chitauro can suspend the registration of
any organization if there are grounds that it has incited people
to engage in stay-aways.
</P>
<P>
Employers would be barred from paying subscription to an
organization which would have been deregistered.
</P>
<P>
People who encourage to engage stay-aways are liable to a
maximum fine of 100,000 Zimbabwean Dollars (about 2,800 U.S.
Dollars) or three years imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The government action comes at a time when actions by the
labor movement, the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions, are blamed
for inflicting huge damages on the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola May Resort to Force Against UNITA: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A Government representative in
the Joint Commission for Angolan Peace Process said here Friday
that his government may have to resort to force in a bid to take
over the areas from the hands of the opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, deputy head of the government delegation to
the joint commission, noted that the government may take an
approach other than a peaceful one to retake these areas seized
back by the National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA).
</P>
<P>
"It may be compulsory or through violent means," Carneiro
said. "That's to say to wipe out the armed forces led by (Jonas)
Savimbi" of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government official admitted that to re-establish
local governments in the areas controlled by the UNITA is far
from easy.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of the areas the Angolan government took over
from the UNITA has been reoccupied by the rebel troops, said
Carneiro.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed his satisfaction with the United Nations
decision to extend the term of the U.N. observers mission in this
southern African country for three more months.
</P>
<P>
Carneiro believed that three months are "enough" to complete
the Angolan peace process together with the breakaway UNITA
Renovation Commission.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Thursday adopted resolutions
demanding the UNITA should immediately disband its troops
unconditionally and withdraw from the areas they reoccupied as
stipulated by the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol which ended the
19-year civil war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process fell into a stalemate as the UNITA
refused to demilitarize all its armed forces and surrender all
the areas it controlled to the hands of the Angolan government in
accordance with the Lusaka peace deal.
</P>
<P>
In September, the Angolan government declared UNITA President
Savimbi as a "war criminal" and decided to cut off any contacts
with the UNITA led by him, saying that it regards a breakaway
group UNITA Renovation Commission as the sole lawful dialogist in
the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
