<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Refuses to Attend Talks Proposed by WTO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States has refused
to attend proposed talks with the European Union on their dispute
over bananas, said trade sources here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. turned down the proposal by Renato Ruggiero,
Director-General of the World Trade Organization (WTO), for U.S.
and EU officials to meet in Geneva on Friday with members of a
panel and an appeals board that ruled that the EU's current banana
import policies had to be changed.
</P>
<P>
Also to have been invited were experts from the WTO's legal
division and trade envoys from countries in Latin America and the
Caribbean with interest in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The WTO chief's proposal came at a time when the EU and the
U.S. are at the edge of a trade war over the EU's rules on banana
imports scheduled to be implemented on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Insisting that the EU revised rules on banana imports still do
not meet WTO criteria, the U.S., backed by five Latin American
banana exporting countries, brought the case to the WTO. If
consultations between the two sides do not lead to a solution, a
panel will be set up to rule the case.
</P>
<P>
There is now no official agenda when the banana case should be
ruled but the U.S. has set a deadline for a panel ruling on
January 15, 1999 and threatened to imposed sanctions worth 1.6
billion U.S. dollars a year on EU goods in February next year
under its trade law "Section 301".
</P>
<P>
The EU believes that the U.S. domestic trade law "Section 301"
itself would be a violation of WTO rules, saying that no one
except the WTO's dispute settlement body can authorize sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
