<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Canada Reach Deal on Farm Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and Canada reached
agreement Friday to ease tensions over farm trade through
stepped-up monitoring of Canada's wheat sales and lower barriers
on American grain and livestock moving northward.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the U.S. will triple the information it
collects on imported Canadian wheat to determine whether the grain
is being sold below cost.
</P>
<P>
U.S. farmers have long claimed that the grain is being dumped
in American markets. Canada denies the charge but has refused to
disclose how the wheat is priced or to limit the amount that is
shipped.
</P>
<P>
Canada also will provide quarterly forecasts of its wheat
shipments, end a quarantine requirement on U.S. hogs and allow
some American grain to be shipped on its railroads to Pacific
ports or sold directly to Canadian elevators.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the two countries will speed the standardization
of regulations for pesticides and animal drugs, and Canada also is
relaxing barriers on imports of U.S. cattle.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreement stops short of meeting the demand by
some farmers and ranchers that Canada limit what it ships to U.S.
markets.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said the
agreement "will help solve many of the problems faced by grain
growers, the cattle industry, and pork producers."
</P>
<P>
The talks started this fall after several governors in Northern
states slowed border crossings by stepping up inspections of
Canadian trucks. Farmers are planning a new round of protests this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
U.S. imports of spring wheat increased 2,000 percent, to 1.45
million tons, from 1990 to 1997, and imports of Canadian durum
were up 57 percent, to 427,600 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves First Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament's lower chamber
on Friday approved the first part of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
planned tax reform amid harsh opposition criticism.
</P>
<P>
Under the legislation, which is expected to get final approval from
the upper house December 18, the income tax rate for low earners drops
to 23.9 per cent from 25.9 per cent and allowances for families with
children rise to 250 marks (150 dollars) from 220 marks.
</P>
<P>
Germany's top marginal income tax rate of 53 per cent will remain
unchanged next year.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder's centre-left government plans modest, step-by-step tax
cuts which will only yield a significant net tax reduction in 2002
when the lowest marginal income tax rate will be cut to 19.9 per cent
and the top rate will drop to 48.5 per cent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government plans to increase taxes on petrol,
natural gas and electricity which it says will be offset by trimming
social welfare payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
