<HEADLINE> Lebanon's New Government Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime
Minister-Designate Salim Hoss formed his cabinet Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet consists of 16 members, only two of whom
worked in the previous government headed by Rafik Hariri, who
refused to accept President Emile Lahoud's request to form a new
government.
</P>
<P>
Hoss, 69, a veteran politician, was named prime minister by
Lahoud two days ago.
</P>
<P>
He said in a news conference that the make-up of the government
is based on the country's traditional power-sharing arrangement,
which divided seats equally between Christians and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
He appointed himself as foreign minister and also minister for
immigrant affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nasser Saidi, vice governor of the central bank, was named as
economy and trade minister, and minister of industry.
</P>
<P>
Walid Jumblatt, Druze leader, and Elie Hobeika, Christian
leader, both former warlords during the country's 1975-1990 civil
war, were excluded from the new government.
</P>
<P>
Only Michel Al-Murr, former Deputy Prime Minister and Interior
Minister, and Suleyman Franjieh, former minister of public health,
were retained in the new government.
</P>
<P>
Murr was appointed deputy prime minister, interior minister and
minister of rural and municipal affairs. Franjieh was named
minister of housing and cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
The newly formed cabinet, which is smaller than the previous
30-man government, was believed by local politicians as a first
step toward administrative reform process pledged by Lahoud in his
inaugural speech on November 24.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet is expected to convene its first session
on Saturday, during which ministers will take their first
group photos and discuss the government future policy.
</P>
<P>
The policy will be submitted to the parliament when Hoss asked
for a vote of confidence for his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The new team is almost certain to win the vote because 95 out
of the 128 lawmakers had told the president this week that they
would back the government led by Hoss. 
</P>
</TEXT>
