<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Over 250 armed Hutu
infiltrators were killed in the past two weeks during military
operations in Ramba and Gaseke communes in Gisenyi Prefecture in
the northwest of Rwanda, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Military sources in the area told RNA that the operations
began on November 16, with security forces of the 305th Brigade
clashing with the militiamen hiding in Gishwati forest.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the first day of fighting, we counted 50 dead
among the Hutu," an officer told RNA, saying that many others may
have been carried away.
</P>
<P>
The operations reportedly went on until the army clashed with
a large group of infiltrators, estimated to be between 1,000 and
1,200 men, in Kimanu sector, Ramba Commune on November 27. Over
200 militiamen were reportedly killed in that single day of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Those killed included an ex-FAR officer, captain Joseph
Nzabonimpa, who was the commander of traffic police before the
1994 genocide. One machine-gun and several assault rifles were
also seized, military sources in Gisenyi said. 
</P>
