<HEADLINE> Rwandan President Denies Ceasefire Agreement in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu has denied that Rwanda was involved in a peace
agreement on the war in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
relating to the cessation of hostilities in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu said Thursday night that no agreement was signed.
Ceasefire is just a wish which did not bind any party, the Rwanda
News Agency Friday quoted Bizimungu as reporting.
</P>
<P>
"All respective parties stood on their positions. There was a
general wish that the peace process continues in order to reach a
solution in the future," Bizimungu said in a press conference at
Kanombe International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu also indicated that Rwanda will keep its troops as
long as its security continues to be threatened by Hutu
extremists, former government soldiers (ex-FAR) and Interahamwe
militia, who are conducting bloody cross-border raids from the
Congolese territory.
</P>
<P>
"Our intervention in Congo is not adventure. It was motivated
by the need to find a solution to the same problems as those we
faced in 1996, the problems of security, the problems of
genocide," Bizimungu underlined.
</P>
<P>
He accused President Laurent Kabila of harboring the Hutu
extremists who committed genocide in Rwanda and who continue
their attacks on the country. Rwanda has accused Kabila's regime
of having formed an alliance with ex-FAR and "Interahamwe", which
is now figting alongside loyalist troops and the South African
Development Community (SADC) forces.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu warned that since there was no ceasefire agreed
upon, warring parties could resume hostilities. Kabila is not
interested in sitting at a negotiating table with the Congolese
rebels, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan president further dismissed cleavages between
Rwanda and Uganda about their intervention in the DRC on the side
of the rebels, saying both countries have a common objective.
</P>
<P>
He said that their intervention in Congo has been motivated by
the need to protect their borders which has been destabilized by
rebels attacking from the Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
