<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Canada Reach Agreement on Farm Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and Canadian trade
officials reached agreement Friday to ease tensions over farm
trade between the world's two largest trade partners.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky noted the
agreement "will help solve many of the problems faced by grain
growers, the cattle industry, and pork producers."
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, the United States will enforce the
monitoring system by tripling the information it collects on
imported Canadian wheat to determine whether the grain is being
sold below cost. U.S. farmers have long claimed that the grain is
being dumped in American markets.
</P>
<P>
However, Canada denies the allegation and has refused to
disclose how the wheat is priced or to limit the amount that is
shipped.
</P>
<P>
Canada also will provide quarterly forecasts of its wheat
shipments, end a quarantine requirement on U.S. hogs and allow
some American grain to be shipped on its railroads to Pacific
ports or sold directly to Canadian elevators.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the two countries, both members of the North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), will speed the standardization of
regulations for pesticides and animal drugs, and Canada also is
relaxing barriers on imports of U.S. cattle.
</P>
<P>
U.S. imports of Spring wheat increased 2,000 percent, to 1.45
million tons, from 1990 to 1997, and imports of Canadian durum
were up 57 percent, to 427,600 tons.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. General Accounting Office (GAO) recently predicted
that more Canadian grain could be headed south to this country in
coming years because of changes in Canada's transportation system
that are making it cheaper to ship into the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
