<HEADLINE> Uganda to Send More Troops to Nomadic Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni announced that the government will deploy more
troops in Karamoja Region in northeastern Uganda to make security
a priority.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the President's Office said Museveni made
the announcement Friday at a public rally in the eastern district
of Moroto.
</P>
<P>
He urged district leaders to work closely with the army to
guarantee security in the vast region where cattle rustlers
operate.
</P>
<P>
The president commended people in Karamoja Region for obeying the
government's directive not to cross to neighboring districts with
guns and urged those raided by the rustlers from Kenya not to
take revenge.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the Ugandan government will contact the Kenyan
side to recover the cattle they lost during the cattle rustling.
</P>
<P>
The Karamoja Region has been neglected in terms of development
by some post-independence governments. It is semi-arid
and characterized by lack of water supply, drought, food shortage
and poor communication.
</P>
<P>
Cattle plays a central role in the socio-economic and
political life of the Karamojong pastoralists. It also provides
food and clothing. Therefore, cattle ownership reflects the
status in the society.
</P>
<P>
The central government has given guns to local defense units
(LDUs) and asked them to keep security there. More than 800 guns
have been provided to the LDUs so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
