<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Urged to Vote in Local Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian leader General
Abdulsalami Abubakar has urged his people to come out in mass to
vote in Saturday's local government election, which is the first
under the military government's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
In a national broadcast Friday on the Nigerian TV Authority
(NTA), Abubakar said Saturday's election will "undoubtedly lay
a solid foundation for the rest of the elections in the
transition program."
</P>
<P>
He urged politicians and political parties to play by the
rule, saying means will not be justified by ends.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar reiterated the Nigerian government's commitment to
hand over power to a democratically elected civilian government
on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We have made solemn commitment to leave a legacy of democracy
based on fairness, equality and justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election will produce 774 local government chairmen
and 8,870 councilors.
</P>
<P>
According to the Independent Electoral Commission (INEC), a
total of 355,077 officials would be employed to work at the
111,430 polling stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
INEC also said that it has distributed 60 million voters'
cards during the voters' registration exercise in October.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election would determine the fate of the country's
nine temporarily registered political parties, as the INEC said
only those securing at least five percent of the total votes cast
in each of at least 24 out of the 36 states and Federal Capital
Territory would be fully registered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
