<HEADLINE> Blair Accepts France's Idea on EU Defense Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Friday agreed with French leaders that the European Union should
have an autonomous capacity for taking actions such as preventing
crises, but fell short of blessing the Western European Union as a
future European defense organization.
</P>
<P>
In a document issued after the 21st Franco-British summit held
in Saint Malo, western France, Blair and French President Jacques
Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said that a capacity to
take action by the EU should rely on credible military forces.
</P>
<P>
The EU should be able to resort to either the NATO forces
stationed in Europe or the national armed forces of European
countries when it decides to take actions in the future, they
said.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union should have an autonomous capacity of
action, relying on the credible military forces, with the means to
use them and being ready to do it in order to respond to
international crises," said the British and French leaders in
their declaration on European defense.
</P>
<P>
Britain said for the first time last month that it would
consider join France, Germany and other European countries in
introducing a defense characteristic to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
London said until then that the defense of Europe should be
completely taken care of by the NATO.
</P>
<P>
France and Britain agreed that the EU should have a capacity
for evaluating the situation, the sources of information, and a
capacity of strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to take into account the present means of the
WEU and "the changing relations between it and the EU.  
</P>
</TEXT>
