<HEADLINE> U.S.-DPRK Talks Resume in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. official said Friday
that talks between the United States and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on the issue of a DPRK underground
facility resumed in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This is to confirm that bilateral talks on suspect underground
construction resumed just shortly after 10 a.m. today," the U.S.
delegation's spokesman Richard Scorza said in a recording phone
message.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has suspected an underground facility in Kumchang-ri,
Taegwan county of North Phyongan Province, as a nuclear one and
asked for inspection, but the DPRK has denied the existence of any
nuclear facility and rejected the inspection demand.
</P>
<P>
The dispute has remained unresolved since the talks began in
Pyongyang on November 16-17 between U.S. special envoy Charles
Kartman and DPRK Vice Foreign Minister Kim Kye-gwan.
</P>
<P>
Calling the U.S. demand a "gave violation" of DPRK sovereignty,
Pyongyang asked the U.S. to make "adequate compensation" before an
inspection is made. But the U.S. rejected the concept of
compensation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. says failure to secure access to inspect the site
could jeopardize a 1994 framework agreement under which the DPRK
will freeze its own nuclear program in return for two modern
nuclear reactors worth more than 4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. spokesman said the new round of talks is scheduled to be
held on December 4-5 in New York and on December 7-8 in
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
