<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank in Support of Malawi's Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved a
92 million U.S. Dollars loan to Malawi in support of the
country's policy reforms in order to accelerate its economic
growth and reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release faxed to Xinhua Friday by the
World Bank, 90 million Dollars of the loan which was approved
Thursday will finance Malawi's fiscal restructuring and
deregulation. The remaining two million Dollars will be for
technical assistance for implementation.
</P>
<P>
The loan will support economic growth and poverty reduction in
Malawi by creating a policy environment that encourages greater
private sector investment and efficiency and helps to realize a
sustaiined and diversified economic growth, said the news
release.
</P>
<P>
It will also support the Malawian government's policies that
redirect its expenditures into social sectors and programs that
benefit the country's poor people, such as basic health care,
primary education and maintenance of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
It is a crucial time to support Malawi, said Ahmad Ahsan,
World Bank's senior country economist for Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Malawi has a good track record of implementing economic
reforms, especially since 1995, but this progress was interrupted
last year by instability and a decline in economic growth, Ahsan
noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that in the last few months, the Malawian government
worked hard to get the country's economy back on track and
demonstrated its commitment by starting to implement wide ranging
policy reforms.
</P>
<P>
He said that these reforms will help to sustain Malawi's good
growth seen in the past few years and to reduce the poverty
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
