<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Works on Containing Deserts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- In its efforts to contain
worldwide deserts, the World Bank has since 1990 financed 159
projects that aim to improve natural resources management in
dry-land areas.
</P>
<P>
Its financing now totals nine billion and leverages additional
nine billion U.S. Dollars, resulting in a total dry-land
investment portfolio exceeding 18 billion Dollars, according to a
World Bank news release available to Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
At present, the bank is taking steps to assist countries in
fighting against desertification.
</P>
<P>
These steps include mainstreaming environmental issues in the
country assistance strategies; maintaining an active program of
lending for development in dry-land areas; and increasing the
emphasis in its rural development activities on sustainable
agricultural systems and dry-land management.
</P>
<P>
Of the earth's surface, 41 percent of the total land area is
being eaten up by ever-expanding arid deserts, affecting more
than 900 million people in 100 countries, some of them are among
the least developed in the world.
</P>
<P>
Annual worldwide economic loss due to desertification is
estimated at 42.3 billion Dollars, the news release cited a
latest World Bank report titled New Opportunities for
Development: The Desertification Convention.
</P>
<P>
The report is being issued to coincide with the Second
Conference of the Parties for the United Nations Convention to
Combat Desertification, which is taking place in Dakar, Senegal,
through December 11.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said in its report that desertification can be
tackled only by fostering broad economic and social changes
directed at its underlying causes.
</P>
<P>
It noted that desertification is not just a physical
phenomenon, but also a result of "inappropriate" economic
policies that undervalue natural resources and encourage misuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
