<HEADLINE> U.S. Hails Europe's Help in Fighting Global Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin and German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine met
here Friday while Rubin applauded European efforts to help fight
global economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Rubin, speaking to reporters before a brief closed-door meeting
with his German counterpart, said Europe had played a constructive
role in fighting world-wide upheaval prompted by Asia's economic
crisis and would no doubt continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
"As we have faced individual issues going through this whole
process, Europe has contributed in a very constructive way and I
have no doubt it will continue to do so," Rubin told reporters
just before meeting Lafontaine, who is on a brief visit to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
"The Europeans have contributed very constructively in what has
been a very complicated set of issues over the last year, most
recently with their bilateral contribution to the support package
for Brazil," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
The international community has put together a 41.5 billion
U.S. dollars dollar rescue package for Brazil, Latin America's
biggest economy. The program includes five billion U.S. dollars
from the United States and more from other bilateral donors.
</P>
<P>
Both Rubin and Lafontaine declined to comment directly on
Thursday's surprise round of interest rate cuts in Europe aimed at
preventing a painful downturn in Europe's economies.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine earlier on Friday said his talks in Washington were
aimed at explaining his government's efforts to stimulate economic
growth and cut sky-high German unemployment rates.
</P>
<P>
He has said in the past that he sees monetary policy as one
tool among several that can be used to boost the economy and he is
a strong advocate of the need for a European-wide jobs initiative.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine is scheduled to meet U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan and the head of the International Monetary Fund,
Michel Camdessus, later on Friday before returning to Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
