<HEADLINE> Hague Defiant Over Sacking Lords Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition
Conservative leader William Hague issued a defiant warning Friday
saying he would sack anyone in his party who behaved like Viscount
Cranborne.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio 5 Live, he said, "Any leader worth his
salt would sack somebody who did what Lord Cranborne did."
</P>
<P>
"I would do the same again. I've had the most tremendous
support from across the party and I've enjoyed myself immensely,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Hague sacked Lord Cranborne Wednesday over his attempt to
strike a deal on Lords reform with Prime Minister Tony Blair,
without telling the rest of the Shadow Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The sacking has left the Conservatives in the Lords in complete
disarray with the whole Tory frontbench team offering their
resignation, which Hague refused.
</P>
<P>
But on Thursday four peers rejected their leader's pleas and
resigned while two other peers left the Tory fold to sit as
independents.
</P>
<P>
In a speech in Cardiff Friday to the Tory team fighting next
year's elections to the new Welsh Assembly, Hague stoutly defended
his actions over what has been one of the party's worst weeks
since the election.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't easy when I refused to accept Labor's deal on the
House of Lords. Some senior colleagues of mine said I should
sacrifice long-term principles for short-term convenience," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"But," he said, "I refused because I wanted to be true to our
principles. I wanted us to be the one party that stands against
the government's constitutional vandalism."
</P>
<P>
"Standing up for your beliefs isn't easy, but it's right. It's
what I came into politics to fight for," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
