<BODY>
<HEADLINE> From Armaments to Motorcycle Magnate (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They decided to depend on themselves for financing, and Cheng
promised to make the first prototype in six months. They turned an
old house into a research institute, and they looked at eight
factories before finding the metal most suitable for making their
prototype.
</P>
<P>
"It was really tough at the beginning, because we had neither the
necessary design drawings nor specific equipment, and 80 percent
of our materials were of no use at all." recalled Cheng.
</P>
<P>
Five prototype motorcycles with the brand name "Jialing"
finally came out in 1979.
</P>
<P>
It was a great success. Their products sold like hot cakes
nationwide, and Cheng was promoted chief engineer in recognition
of his outstanding performance.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Jialing Group has taken the lead among China's
motorcycle manufacturers. Its productivity has been rising at the
rate of 30 percent a year since it made an arrangement with 11
other firms for spare-parts production, and it made 2 billion yuan
(240 million U.S.dollars) in profits in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Many former armament enterprises have followed suit by
shifting from producing daily-use products and electrical
appliances to the manufacturing of motorcycles, mini-vehicles and
heavy-duty trucks.
</P>
<P>
Now that the national motorcycle market has reached the
saturation point, Cheng has decided to start the third phase of
his career by developing agricultural machinery to serve the vast
number of China's rural people. "We must always be
market-oriented," said Cheng.
</P>
<P>
Cheng explained that he has begun to learn computers now
because computers have become the primary design tools, replacing
the rulers and pencils of yesterday, and one must keep up with a
fast-changing world if one wants to make steady progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
