<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> From Armaments to Motorcycle Magnate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Cheng Xingming, an
armament-industry engineer 20 years ago and now a motorcycle
magnate, decided to learn computers at the age of 60.
</P>
<P>
While engaged in the technological developments of the armament
industry and motorcycle production, Cheng did his work with rulers
and pencil and paper from the time he was assigned to the China
Jialing Group, a key weapons manufacturer in southwestern China's
Chongqing City, after his graduation from Chongqing University in
1964.
</P>
<P>
"I wish my study of computer technology could help me with a
third success in my life-long industrial career," he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1980s, Cheng was a specialist in the manufacturing
of cartridges, and his first success was in the weapons industry.
</P>
<P>
He was the first to use steel instead of copper in shell
case production, and the armor-piercing shell he invented was
awarded the state's gold prize.
</P>
<P>
However, he had to shift from war-products to civil industry at
the turn of the 1970s and early 80s when China's weapons factories
were required to transform their production lines into ones for
civil uses.
</P>
<P>
Jialing had only around 58 million yuan (7 million U.S.dollars)
worth of fixed assets, and less than 20 million yuan (2.4 million
U.S.dollars) of annual output value at the beginning of the
reforms, and it was operating at a loss.
</P>
<P>
"We felt quite distressed and were at a loss at that time, and
our factory's prospects seemed totally bleak. It was just like a
stranded ship," Cheng recalled.
</P>
<P>
At first, Cheng and the other engineers wanted to cooperate
with Honda, Yamaha, and Suzuki, three well-established Japanese
enterprises, on developing motorcycles for civilian use. The
Japanese offered to set up an assembly line for them, with an
annual output capacity of 20,000 motorcycles, and a five-year
investment of 50 million U.S.dollars, but 20 percent of the key
spare parts would still had to be imported from Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
