<HEADLINE> Chiang Kai-shek's Hometown Luring Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Fenghua in east China's
Zhejiang Province used to be a Mecca for visitors from Taiwan
Province because it is the hometown of Chiang Kai-shek, late leader
of the Kuomintang and head of the Nationalist government from 1928
to 1949.
</P>
<P>
But local people have turned it into a hot spot for overseas
investment as well.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, when the first overseas-funded company was set up
in Fenghua, this county-level city has invested heavily in
infrastructure and built many urban roads and apartment
buildings, as well as a modern telephone network with a capacity
of 100,000 lines.
</P>
<P>
To improve the investment environment, the city government
invited architects to create plans for an urban expansion program,
and residents were asked to make every effort to maintain a sound
business atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
These efforts have paid off. By the end of this October, the
county-level city had approved the opening of 236 firms with
capital totaling 514 million U.S. dollars, including 168 million
dollars from overseas investors. 
</P>
