<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies Blocking U.N. Arms Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq denied on Saturday an
accusation by U.N. deputy chief arms inspector Charles Duelfer
that Iraq has blocked a U.N. arms inspection team from entering a
site.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency, Hussam
Mohameed Ameen, head of the Iraqi liaison with the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) which provides escorts to U.N. arms
inspectors, said Duelfer's accusation "is a sheer lie."
</P>
<P>
Iraq did not block U.N. arms inspectors from going where
they wanted to go, Ameen affirmed.
</P>
<P>
On November 25, a 12-member UNSCOM team wanted to carry out a
surprise inspection to a base which belongs to a foreign country,
said Ameen. However, he did not mention which country it is.
</P>
<P>
U.N. arms inspectors' access to this foreign base should be
discussed between heads of the UNSCOM team and the base, said
Ameen. He added the Iraqi side is very prudent on the matter of
this sort.
</P>
<P>
After three hours of representations with the foreign base in
which the Iraqi side is not involved at all, head of the UNSCOM
team Mario Baycol decided not to enter the base, said Ameen.
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned UNSCOM team has carried out inspections
to 15 sites, including governmental organizations, factories and
tobacco companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ameen said that he was surprised to hear Duelfer's accusation,
stressing that Duelfer was deliberately trying to distort the
truth.
</P>
<P>
In mid-November, Iraq announced unconditional resumption of
cooperation with UNSCOM which it suspended last August and thus it
narrowly escaped a U.S.-led military attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
