<HEADLINE> Feature: Bangkok Ready to Orchestrate Big Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Red carpet is being rolled over
for the King's presence Sunday night at the Royal Main Stadium
while the mascots of elephant are smiling from every corner of
Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The colors of the 41 members of the Olympic Council of Asia
(OCA) are dancing in the breeze along the express ways above the
metropolitan which habors a population of six million.
</P>
<P>
One day before the opening ceremony, every sign justifies that
Bangkok, casting off the shadow of its most severe economic tumble
in decades, is ready for the latest sports festival of the
continent, the 13th Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
After the "Black July" last year when Thai baht was forced to
devalue, Thailand that was struck first in the mire of financial
crisis, was plunged into doubts upon its capability to host the
biggest sports gala before the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
However, as if in a gesture to nod for the Asian Games, the
Thai economy is showing signs of recovery as its currency climbed
to 35 baht to one U.S. dollar from 41 a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand index rocketed to nearly 400
points from the lowest 200 points not so long ago, and over three
billion U.S. dollars have flown into the country since the
beginning of the year, manifesting more and more foreign investors
are gaining confidence in the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
Both the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the Thai
government estimated that Thailand will bottom out of the crisis
by the end of the year and its Gross Domestic Product will see a
growth of one percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Coming at such a time and coinciding with King Bhumibol
Adulyadej's 71st birthday on Saturday, the Asian Games is becoming
a festival for the Thai people.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the Thai people have every reason to celebrate as the
Games is to kick off at the peak of the tourism season, bringing
about 80 million baht (2.2 million dollars) daily to the industry.
</P>
<P>
Hotels in downtown Bangkok are fully occupied, and the industry
is expected to earn 300 million baht (8.3 million dollars) during
the fortnight meet.
</P>
<P>
Small peddlers are among the most enthusiastic in welcoming the
Games for they have already seen their businesses boomed.
</P>
<P>
A balloon peddler near the Sanam Luang square (the Royal
Ground), who only gave his name as Chainat, said he has met more
customers now than before.
</P>
<P>
"Usually, I earned less than 100 baht (2.7 dollars) every day,
but now more than 150 baht (about 4 dollars)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Songtot, who quitted his job in a factory to sell ice-creams
outside the Main Press Center building in Muang Thong Thani Sport
Complex, said his business is not as satisfactory as expected.
</P>
<P>
"But I hope it will become better when the Games begins," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
