<HEADLINE> Party Launches Campaign to Improve Work Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- China will undertake a campaign
to improve the work style of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
over the next year.
</P>
<P>
The program called "three stresses" will target leading
officials above the county level through criticism, self-criticism
and education, with stresses on studying theory, increasing
political consciousness, and cultivating healthy trends.
</P>
<P>
According to a telephone-television conference held by the
Party Central Committee here this afternoon, the program will also
help officials consolidate their belief in socialism with Chinese
characteristics, act in unison with the Party Central Committee,
and ensure the implementation of the Party's policies.
</P>
<P>
Hu Jintao, a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, said during the conference
that this decision is very significant because it will serve to
improve the cohesion and effectiveness of the Party's
organizations and strengthen their relationship to the people.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu, serious problems exist among some officials,
including some who hold important and leading positions.
</P>
<P>
He said Party general secretary Jiang Zemin has instructed that
Party officials should be educated, and that this program is of
great importance as China faces both opportunity and challenge at
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Officials must exercise their powers in a correct way,
eliminate bureaucracy, and fight against corruption, according to
Hu, adding that the campaign will deal with pressing problems in
the Party's work, especially those which have aroused concerns
among the public and hindered the reforms.
</P>
<P>
Hu noted that a democratic atmosphere must be created in the
campaign, and officials should modestly listen to the criticisms
and suggestions of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
The conference was presided over by Wei Jianxing, secretary of
the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection of the CPC.
</P>
</TEXT>
