<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmer Who Improves People's Diets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Wang Leyi, a farmer from China's
Shandong Province, could never imagine a "white revolution" he
started in 1989 would change the lives of multi-million Chinese
who could never get fresh vegetables in winter.
</P>
<P>
Northern Chinese used to live on Chinese cabbage and potatoes
in the winter months, but now the "white revolution", the
cultivation of vegetables in greenhouses covered by
plastic-sheeting, is now common all over northern China.
</P>
<P>
China's total vegetable output nearly doubled in the past
decade, and per capita vegetable consumption reached 253 kilograms
in 1997, about average in the world.
</P>
<P>
Wang's hometown of Shouguang, near the Bohai Sea, has 200,000
of the covered greenhouses and is an important vegetable producer
for Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wang's greenhouse has thick earth walls on three sides. At
night, the plastic sheeting is covered with rice thick straw to
hold the warmth.
</P>
<P>
Each greenhouse costs about 7,000 yuan, but it produces several
10,000 yuan in profits.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is in his sixties, has had more than 500,000 visitors
from across the country since 1990 and he also has travelled to
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region and Gansu Province to help
farmers there with vegetable production.
</P>
<P>
Wang attributes his success to his "active thinking". He
explains that the idea came from a kilogram of cucumbers one of
his relatives gave to his mother during Spring Festival of
1988. He says he was surprised to see cucumbers those icy days the
first time in his life, and at that moment had an idea about how
farmers could do something during the slack season.
</P>
<P>
China has covered greenhouses producing several dozen types of
vegetables on 933,000 hectares of land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
