<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research Confirming Chinese Flood Legend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars say they have
proven that catastrophic floods did take place in the Yangtze
River Valley about 4,000 years ago and that the ancient legend of
"Dayu Regulating the Floods of the Yangtze River" is true.
</P>
<P>
Professor Zhu Cheng at Nanjing University believes that the
greatest flood coincided with the period the legend describes.
</P>
<P>
Dayu was the reputed founder of the Xia Dynasty and led the
Chinese in controlling floodwaters in ancient China. He is still
worshipped by people in the Yangtze and Yellow river valleys.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said at a symposium on China's environment that he and his
colleagues used carbon dating to study hundreds of ancient relic
sites on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
They say that from 7,000 to 2,000 years ago, there was one
large flood every 500-1,000 years and they found that there were
altogether 7 catastrophic floods from 8,000 B.C.to 1,300 B.C.,
during the Shang and Zhou dynasties (1,600-1,000 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The flood 4,000 years ago was the greatest, they decided, based
on phenomenal interruptions in many strata. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV-Shopping Booms in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Nowadays, many Chinese tired
of spending so much of their time shopping have found a new and
convenient way to accomplish this chore -- simply tuning in to one
of the many TV-shopping programs and making a phone call to place
their order.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, when the Beijing Television Station premiered
China's first TV-shopping program, on-air business has been
flourishing in China, mostly in the major cities. Currently, over
200 local television stations nationwide offer TV-shopping
programs.
</P>
<P>
However, this modern method of direct selling has drawn as many
controversial comments as it has sales, both from customers and
officials.
</P>
<P>
While many people like the convenience, others are put off
by what they see as irrationally high prices, poor quality,
false advertising, and poor delivery service.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some television viewers have blasted some TV-shopping
ads for health and body-building products for being sexually
provocative. These problems have led to a cooler attitude toward
TV-shopping this year.
</P>
<P>
However, most local and overseas experts are optimistic about
the prospects for the fledgling business, noting that China, the
most populous country in the world, boasts 75 million cable-TV
subscribers, and a total of 1.09 billion TV-viewers.
</P>
<P>
They urge local TV-shopping operators to improve their services
to win back customers, and believe that the government should take
steps to standardize the business. A non-governmental agency also
should be set up as soon as possible to supervise this sector,
they say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
