<HEADLINE> Northeast China Expects To Be Leading Green-Food Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of
Sciences plans to cooperate with provinces in northeast China to
develop green food and turn the region into China's largest green
food base.
</P>
<P>
They expect to turn 12 to 20 counties into leading producers of
organic vegetables, fruit and poultry over the next seven years,
said Li Zhensheng, director of the agricultural experts committee
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China, which includes Heilongjiang, Jilin and
Liaoning provinces and four leagues in eastern Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, covers an area of 1.24 million square
kilometers, equivalent to the combined area of Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
The region has won state approval for the production of 216
kinds of green food, accounting for one fifth of the country's
total. The annual output value of green food in Heilongjiang
Province alone totaled 760 million yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
Overall, China has sown more than 2.6 million hectares of green
food, and the country's export value of green food averages 20
billion U.S. dollars a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
