<HEADLINE> Palestinians Held Demonstrations across West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinians continued
anti-Israel demonstrations across the West Bank on Saturday, days
before U.S. President Bill Clinton sets foot on the soil under
Palestinian self-rule.
</P>
<P>
Near the Ariel El Jewish settlement north of Ramallah, hundreds
of Palestinians tried to break into the settlement but were fought
back by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers fired tear gas and rubber-coated bullets towards
the demonstrators, but no one was reported hurt, according the
Voice of Palestine (VOP).
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, south of the West Bank, thousands of Palestinians
took part in a demonstration organized by the Palestinian
Liberation Front, which told the protesters that the front will
never stop fighting against the Israeli occupation, VOP said.
</P>
<P>
In Bethlehem, south of Jerusalem, Palestinian demonstrators
clashed with Israeli security forces near the Rachel's Tomb. The
demonstrators denounced Israel's intention to continue holding the
Palestinian prisoners in its jails.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian prisoners in various Israeli jails are scheduled to
start a hunger strike Saturday evening in a bid to force Israel to
release them as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is to visit Gaza to address the Palestinian National
Council on the cancellation of provisions in the Palestinian
national charter calling for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the implementation of the Wye peace accord
signed in October between Israel and the Palestinians. However,
progress in the implementation has been far from satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians in the territories have been demonstrating
against Israel's continued detention of thousands of Palestinian
prisoners and urged for their release according to the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
Israel has released the first band of 250 Palestinian
prisoners, out of the 750 stipulated in the Wye accord. But the
Palestinian authority said about half of the freed were common
criminals, not political prisoners as agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
Israel said it will never set free those Palestinians "with
Israeli blood on their hands," particularly members of the Islamic
resistance group Hamas that has been responsible for a series of
attacks against Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
