<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Has "Illiteracy-Free" District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh, a country with nearly
half of its 127-million population illiterate, now has a
"illiteracy-free" district, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing Magura as illiteracy-free at a massive public rally
in the district, Hasina said the government chose education as a
major strategy for poverty alleviation as illiteracy was one of
the main impediments in the way of overall development in
Bangladesh, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Magura, some 110 kilometers southwest of Dhaka, the capital
city, was backward in respect of the overall socio-economic
development in the country, so the government undertook a program
to remove illiteracy from the district, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The program included poverty alleviation, eradication of
illiteracy, sanitation, afforestation, environment, health and
family planning.
</P>
<P>
She hoped that the district would become an example as a basis
for socio-economic development for the whole country.
</P>
<P>
An overall literacy drive started in the district in March last
year, under which 200,100 elderly men and women had been given
education so far.
</P>
<P>
The country's struggle against illiteracy was praised all over
the world, she said, as shown by its achievement of the
International Literacy Award 1998 for its success in the field of
primary and mass education.
</P>
<P>
To remove illiteracy by the year 2006, the Bangladeshi
government has pledged to set up at least one school in each of
the 59,900 villages across the country, where 57.4 percent of its
people aged above 15 are not able to read and write. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
