<HEADLINE> Pakistan Nets 200m Dollars in Trade with CARs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has netted a total
of 200 million U.S. dollar balance in its trade with the Central
Asian Republics (CAR) in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan exported goods worth 218 million dollars to five CARs
of Uzbekstan, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan
in the past four years and imported various items from the five
countries worth of 18 million dollars, sources from the
International Trade Organization said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the quantum of trade between Pakistan and
CARs had been moving around 50 million dollars per annum because
there was no proper channel for the transportation of goods by
road and by air.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only passengers carry with them a small quantity of
goods which they sell in CARs and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Pakistan and CARs must establish a proper
route to expand their bilateral trade, the sources said, adding
that present available option is the launching of cargo service by
the Pakistan International Airline (PIA) on this route that can
help boost up trade.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and the Central Asian Republics have a vast scope of
expansion in their trade. However, it would be possible only when
they succeed in establishing a regular route, either by road or by
air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
