<HEADLINE> Nepal, India to Extend Transit Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and India have agreed
to extend the existing bilateral transit treaty which expires
Saturday by one month or till the date of its formal renewal as
they cannot renew it before its expiry, the official RSS news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Necessary instructions are being issued to ensure that the
movement of Nepal's traffic-in transit between the Calcutta port
of India and the 15 mutually agreed entry and exit points along
the border will continue smoothly, RSS said, quoting a joint press
release.
</P>
<P>
It said that additional transit routes, including that through
Phulbari in northeast India, will also continue.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to renew the bilateral transit treaty
signed on December 6, 1991 with mutually agreed modifications.
</P>
<P>
But they failed by the deadline because they could not find a
mutually suitable time, The Kathmandu Post daily said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
RSS said that the mutually agreed draft transit treaty to be
signed shortly will have simplified procedures for the transit of
Nepal's import and export cargoes.
</P>
<P>
As a land-locked country, Nepal depends largely on the transit
routes through India for foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
