<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Golfer on Course to Title at Omega PG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean golfer Kang
Wook-soon remained on course for a remarkable Hong Kong double
after a four under par 66 gave him a four-shot lead here on
Saturday going into the final round of the 500,000 U.S. dollars
Omega PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
Kang, winner last week of the Perrier Hong Kong Open, earned
four birdies in a flawless display of golf and heads the leader
board from Chinese Taipei's Hsieh Chin-sheng, who returned a
three under 67 despite a double bogey at the last hole.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Boonchu Ruangkit and Chinese number one Zhang
Lian-wei shared the third place at eight under par after carding
66 and 68 respectively over the 6,096-yeard Clearwater Bay layout.
</P>
<P>
Kang toured the front half in 32 thanks to birdies from six
feet at the second and fifth, and moved to three under for the
day following a 15-foot birdie at the short par four ninth. The
1996 Omega Order of Merit champion made sure of a four-shot
cushion with an eight-foot birdie at the par five 18th.
</P>
<P>
"I'm hitting the ball better than ever at the moment, and
although there are some very good players behind me on the leader
board I'll try to just focus on my own game tomorrow," said Kang,
a two-time winner on the 1996 Omega Tour.
</P>
<P>
If Kang can keep his rivals at bay in the Omega Tour's
season-closing event, he will become the first player in Asian
PGA history to win back-to-back events.
</P>
<P>
Kang could also become the first player to twice win the Omega
Order of Merit, though his chances will depend on the final round
performances of, among others, Englishmen Ed Fryatt and Chris
Williams, as well as Shaun Michael of America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
