<BODY>
<HEADLINE> District Sub-clan Fightings End in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The fighting in Sakow
District between the two Rahanwein sub-clans of Moallimweyne and
Geladleh has now stopped after a peace resolution negotiated by
Rahanwein and Marehan clansmen has came into effect Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from the region, cease-fire was achieved
after a 40-member delegation from Bardera District including
traditional elders from the various Rahanwein clans and a
53-member delegation from the religious group of Jamea Jawarey
have intervened into the serious bloodletting in the district.
</P>
<P>
At a three-day meeting in the town of Sakow, an unconditional
cease-fire was concluded and the two sides signed a six point
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohamed Sheikh Abdusalam, the chief elder of the
Geladleh sub-clan and Madey Malaq Ahmed from the Moallimweyne
signed the document on behalf of their respective sub-clans in
Sakow District Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreed points include the cessation of hostility, the
separation of armed men and their redeployment from the affected
towns and villages where the clashes had spread to.
</P>
<P>
The important points in the pact also include the return of
animal and materials looted during the fighting to their rightful
owners and collective punitive measures to be taken against any
side that violates the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
According to the local authorities in Sakow District, the
accord was reached after serious talks began at the grass-roots
level following the failure of several cease-fire attempts late
last month by official talks between the two sides here in
Mogadishu and in the region as well.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 people died and at least 150 other were wounded since
the fighting started some three weeks ago over job opportunities
in a Swedish aid agency -- Swedish Church Relief. The fighting
had erased three villages and caused considerable damages to the
town of Sakow itself.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people who fled to the nearby villages and towns
are reported to have been on the move again toward Sakow District
Saturday after the delegates have called the people via VEP
radios and all other possible means to return to their houses.
</P>
</TEXT>
