<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Japan to Fare up for Asiad Marathon Hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The women's marathon on Sunday
is fated to be a sensational hit for the 13th Asian Games as its
first gold medal will probably be grabbed either by present
sportspower China or former giant Japan.
</P>
<P>
Pan Jinhong, Chinese national champion who won the 1997 Beijing
marathon with a personal best of two hours 28 minutes 39 seconds,
is tipped to spearhead a scarce field of 13 runners in the Games'
most grueling race.
</P>
<P>
Compatriot Wang Yanfang, eighth finisher of the London marathon
early this year, is believed to create enough cusion for Pan to
attain the glory for China, who is hailed to have a lion's share
in the quadrennial gala on the world's most populous continent.
</P>
<P>
Shang Xiutang, generay secretary of the Chinese Athletics
Association, said: "Pan is in a solid shape and has a sound chance
for victory though I am not ready to predict her a sure shot."
</P>
<P>
Wang sprained her ankle before coming to Bangkok but the injury
is not serious enough to cost her medal hope, Shang explained.
</P>
<P>
Pan and Wang, both started their marathon careers 10 years ago,
had been training for weeks in Guangzhou and Xishuangbanna of
Yunan Province, where the climate was thought similar to Bangkok,
Shang said.
</P>
<P>
"But it's really too hot in Bangkok," Shang said. "A runner
usually loses her weight of three kilograms after a marathon race
in Beijing, but will lose four here," Shang said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese runners are full of confidence despite the
fact that the steaming weather here may affect their timings,
Shang said, adding that "Both Pan and Wang felt no pressure and
they will fight to their best. "
</P>
<P>
Yet, the Chinese athletics top official was quick to say that
"the Japanese runners enjoy their edges."
</P>
<P>
Nooko Takahashi is the hot favorite for Japan, who enjoys an
awesome personal best of 2:25.48 and has won three races on home
soils this year.
</P>
<P>
"I know nothing about the Chinese runners as well as those from
other teams," said the 26-year-old Japanese at a press conference
this afternoon, "I only want to do my best to take the gold
medal."
</P>
<P>
Coach Koshio Koide is pinning high hopes upon his protegee to
win the "most important gold medal" of the Games.
</P>
<P>
"In our full preparation, she has been training very hard in
the past a few months, and she told me she is to stand atop the
podium," said Koide, also coach of Hiromi Suzuki, winner of the
Athens World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Suzuki has skipped the Asian Games to focus on the World
Championships next year and the Sydney Olympics in 2000, Koide
said.
</P>
<P>
But Japan has another fortune as Tomoko Kai registered a
personal best of 2:28.13, only next to both Takahashi and Pan
Jinhong.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old warned against any surprise if she eventually
becomes the winner, saying "I will concentrate on the race and I
have the confidence to run."
</P>
<P>
At an unusally early hour of six thirty, the Bangkok Games'
curtain-raising gunfire will be echoed above a highway, 33km north
of the Athletes Village set up within Thammasal University campus,
signalling the first strides of the 42.195-km classic test of
indurance and stamina.
</P>
<P>
The runners will stride across the Chaopraya River and kick
forward for some 33 kilometes beforing their final show-up at
Thammasal University.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, Kyrgyzstan, Laos, DPR Korea, Thailand, Tajikistan
and South Korea also field in their runners although they are
widely thought of lack of the calibre to challenge the four
Chinese and Japanese women.
</P>
<P>
As the competitors will have to run against the scorching sun
along the most stages, "I think the winner will have a clocking
between 2:26:00 and 2:32:00," said coach Koide, "But the time is
not important, we only want to win." 
</P>
</TEXT>
