<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Yan Unsure to Win Four Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese swimming prodigy Chen
Yan said here on Saturday that she is not sure of winning all the
four individual events she enters in the 13th Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who set a world record of four minutes 34.79 seconds in
the women's 400-meter individual medley in the Chinese National
Games in October, 1997, will take part in the 200m and 400m
individual medleys, the 400m and 800m freestyles and the 4x200
freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old swimmer said: "Everybody expects me to win all
the four golds, or even a fifth in the relay, but I'm not sure of
that because I am not in the top form."
</P>
<P>
Chen, who won two golds and one silver in the World
Championships in Perth, Australia in January, said she is not
aiming to beat any world record in the Games, which is to open on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"My form now is rather medicore, so it is impossible for me to
break any world record," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
