<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Arrives in Ankara for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak arrived here at noon Saturday for a two-day state visit to
Turkey at the invitation of President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents are expected to hold talks on regional and
international issues as well as bilateral ties between Turkey and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's visit came two months after he helped defuse a crisis
between Ankara and Damascus over the Kurdish issue.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president shuttled between Ankara and Damascus in
early October to ease tension heightened after Turkey threatened
to launch military strikes against Syria if Damascus continues to
support the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), outlawed in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The mediation efforts later produced a deal under which Syria
pledged not to allow PKK activities on its territory. Turkish
determination is believed to have forced PKK leader Abdullah
Ocalan to leave Syria.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was detained by the Italian police upon his arrival in
Rome by a Russian Airlines passenger plane on November 12.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry has said that it expected the PKK
issue would be on the agenda of Mubarak's visit.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old separatist war for
self rule in southeastern Turkey, which has claimed over 37,000
lives since August 1984.
</P>
<P>
Italy rejected a Turkish warrant for the extradition of the
Kurdish rebel chief, saying its laws forbade extradition to a
country where the suspect may face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said
that he backed the European Union's initiative to try Ocalan
before an international tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
