<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aziz Leaves for Moscow to Seek Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz left here Saturday for Moscow on a two-day visit to
Russia over the situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
His visit came a day after Richard Butler, head of the United
Nations Special Commission for disarming Iraq (UNSCOM), visited
Moscow, a move widely believed to seek Russian support on the
Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Butler has requested that Iraq hand over immediately a document
seen at its airforce headquarters last July and other documents
concerning Iraq's chemical weapons used during the Iraq-Iran war
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused Butler of trying to create new pretexts for the
United States to launch military attacks on Iraq, calling his
request "provocative."
</P>
<P>
Iraq said it is considering disclosing relevant portions of the
documents on its airforce in the presence of the United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's Special Envoy Prakash Shah as well
as UNSCOM inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Posuvaluk said recently
that Moscow thought it necessary to resume full cooperation
between Iraq and UNSCOM without any provocation from either party
so that a comprehensive review on Iraq's compliance with the
U.N. resolutions could be conducted in two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The crippling sanctions imposed on Iraq following its 1990
invasion of Kuwait cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM verifies that
Iraq is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Aziz's visit to Moscow at this
time is aimed at drumming up Russian support for an early
commencement of the comprehensive review proposed by Kofi Annan so
that the U.N. sanctions could be lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
