<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vyguzova Tipped to Break China's Domination in Diving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- World champion Irina Vyguzova
of Kazakhstan has the calibre to break China's domination in the
diving competition by winning one gold in the approaching 13th
Asian Games, said Kazakhstan diving coach Yuriy Grishin here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Vyguzova, who took the three-meter springboard gold by beating
China's ace women diver Guo Jingjing in the FINA World Cup in
Sydney in January, was considered as the sole threat to the
Chinese divers in the Games to kick off on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We need a diving gold medal," said Grishin through an
interpretor, "Irina has the chance to beat the Chinese divers,
especially in the three-meter springboard."
</P>
<P>
Chinese diving coach Zhou Jihong, who won China's first Olympic
diving gold in the 1984 Olympic Games, also acknowledged that
Vyguzova will stand in her divers' way to glory.
</P>
<P>
"She is an experienced, consistent diver and will pose some
threats to us," Zhou said, "But if my divers make no big mistakes
in the competition, Irina will have no chance."
</P>
<P>
Guo Jingjing was confident that Vyguzova will bring her no
trouble. "I will undoubtedly beat her this time," she added,
"China will make a clear sweep of all the four golds at stake."
</P>
<P>
Yet, Vyguzova seemed unsure of her chance against the Chinese
divers. "Yes I am confident to win," she said, then changed her
tone immediately, "but not this time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
