<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Courts Urged by President to Tackle Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Indian President K. R.
Narayanan Saturday expressed serious concern over a backlog of 30
million cases in various courts in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on judicial reforms here, he said that
the government and judiciary should take steps to tackle all these
cases on a "war footing".
</P>
<P>
The law as it affects women and the weaker sections of society
needs to be reformed and where there are laws already enacted,
they must be faithfully followed by the executive and judiciary,
he said.
</P>
<P>
A combination of factors has conspired to make law a
time-consuming process-- the intricacies of procedures, the
ingenuity of lawyers in prolonging cases, even the indifferent
judges, and the unending process of appeals that is available, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
