<HEADLINE> Armed Forces Must be on Crisis Alert: Malaysian King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Supreme Head of
State Tuanku Ja'afar Saturday called on the armed forces to be on
the alert for eventualities arising from the current regional
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The King, who is also supreme commander of the Malaysian armed
forces, said the military should optimize use of assets in their
inventory as part of its austerity drive.
</P>
<P>
But this should not mean that the armed forces could compromise
military exercises and its preparedness to defend the nation, the
King said at a passing-out parade and commissioning of 103 short
service cadet officers at the Military Academy here.
</P>
<P>
"In fact during situations like this we must be more alert
because history had proven that economic problems can result in
misunderstanding between neighboring countries and within the
region, with the possibility of conflicts. Although it is better
for problems to be solved through the negotiating table, we must
be in readiness to face the possibilities," the King said.
</P>
<P>
"For this, exercises must continue to be carried out while
assets should be fully utilized," said Tuanku Ja'afar.
</P>
<P>
Loyalty to the superior authorities especially in a disciplined
organization like the armed forces was of utmost importance, the
King said, adding ignoring this aspect might create a
communication gap between the superior authority and subordinates
with the possibility of orders being misconstrued and
misunderstood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
