<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Beat Courageous Laos 6-1 in Asiad Football </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran met a stiff resistence
earlier in the first half but still prevailed 6-1 over underdogs
Laos in the Asiad soccer tournament at Si Sa Ket on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian team, which had as many as six players who took
part in the World Cup finals, had a slow start and failed
dominate the match early in the match.
</P>
<P>
The first 20 minutes turned to be an even match as the
Iranians struggled to get control of the mid-field but the Laos
team fought hard to keep their goal safe.
</P>
<P>
But at the 23rd minute, S. Mosavi-Hasanzadeh beat the
off-side trap to put Iran 1-0 ahead. He went on to score again
for Iran 6 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
After taking the 2-0 lead, the Iranian team appeared relaxed
and the Laos team took the chance to narrow the gap to 2-1 just
before the interval.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian team were furious about the goal they conceded
and in the second half, they took advantage of their height and
constantly threatened the Laos goal.
</P>
<P>
Ali-Reza Mansourian made it 3-1 for Iran and Darioush
Yazdani sent home a long-distance shot at the 80th minute.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian team then scored two more goals to wrap up the
match 6-1.
</P>
<P>
For the Laos team, the defeat is no humiliation as long as
they could score a goal against the powerful Iranian team.
</P>
<P>
The win put Iran into the second stage of the Asian Games
soccer tournament with two straight wins. They beat Kazakhstan
2-0 in their first group H match.
</P>
<P>
In another match played on Saturday, defending champions
Uzbekistan trounced Mongolia 15-0 to take the first place of
Group G. Kuwait finished second and also earned a place in the
second stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Hot-line to Link China's Mainland, Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A hot-line telephone link
will be established and provide constant service round the clock
between the police departments in China's mainland and the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), it was announced here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here by Zhu Entao, assistant to Chinese
minister of public security and head of a visiting delegation from
the ministry, after the second bilateral meeting here on
cooperation between the police departments of China's mainland and
SAR.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral meeting was held in accordance with an agreement
reached by the two parties when a Hong Kong SAR police delegation
visited Beijing in May this year. Such meetings are to be held
twice a year, one in Beijing and the other in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Agenda of the meeting include an exchange of information and
related figures on public security, issues of common interest such
as fight against underground society, drug trafficking, commercial
crimes and illegal immigration, said Hui Ki-On, Hong Kong SAR's
commissioner of police.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two parties had met 25 times before Hong
Kong's handover in July last year, greatly contributing to the
smooth procession of the handover, Zhu said after Saturday's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the concept of "One Country, Two Systems",
the cooperation between the mainland and Hong Kong SAR has been
expanded and consolidated after the handover, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"The concrete discussions during the second bilateral meeting
in Hong Kong were very fruitful and I am happy with the results,"
Zhu continued.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 criminal suspects wanted in the SAR have been
extradited from the mainland and 17 stolen Hong Kong vehicles
returned this year. The police departments of the two parties
have consolidated their cooperation in fighting against organized
crimes and cross-border crimes which mainly involved China's
Guangdong Province, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral efforts will be made to improve cooperation on issues
such as border and traffic control, education, training and
scientific equipment.
</P>
<P>
There are some differences in the laws adopted at the mainland
and SAR, which "need and can be solved through consultation and
legal processions," Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
