<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak on Mediation Between Turkey and Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said the goal of his mediation between Turkey and Syria in October
was to help them solve their disputes in a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Turkey's Milliyet newspaper before his
visit to Ankara due Saturday, Mubarak disclosed behind-the-scenes
contacts when tensions mounted between Ankara and Damascus, the
Egyptian Mail newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
When the crisis reached its climax, he got messages from Saudi
Arabia and other Gulf countries asking him to step in to act as a
mediator, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey threatened military actions against Syria in October to
stop what it denounced as Syria's support for the separatist
Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been fighting for independence
in southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that he hurried to Turkey and got assurances from
President Suleyman Demirel that the door was still open for a
diplomatic solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He then immediately consulted with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad on the issue in a telephone conversation and flew from
Ankara to Damascus for further talks, the Egyptian leader said.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate goal of his efforts was to bring Turkey and Syria
to the negotiating table in a bid to head off a regional military
conflict, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Ankara and Damascus signed an agreement in late October in
which Syria pledged to close PKK camps in Syria and not to allow
PKK militants to launch cross-border attack against Turkey from
its soil.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak urged Turkey to move forward in relations with Syria
after the two neighbors succeeded in resolving the thorny issue in
a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
During the upcoming visit to Turkey, Mubarak will hold talks
with Demirel on regional issues, including the Middle East peace
process, and ways of promoting bilateral relations, the Egyptian
Mail said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
