<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Close to Total Control of Hib Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States is close
to totally controlling the serious invasive disease on children
caused by Hemophilia influenza b (Hib) bacteria, the U.S. Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Only 258 cases of invasive Hib, such as bacterial meningitis,
were reported to the CDCP in 1997, compared with 20,000 cases in
children under age 5 were reported in the early 1980s, CDCP said
in the latest issue of Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, case rates have dropped from 41 per 100,000
children in 1987 to 1.3 per 100,000 in 1997, CDCP added.
</P>
<P>
"Hib vaccine should be valued as a way to prevent the deadly
disease that less than a generation ago plagued our youngest
children," said CDCP director Dr. Jeffery P. Koplan.
</P>
<P>
Before Hib vaccine became widely available, according to U.S.
federal statistics, one in 200 U.S. pre-school children developed
serious complications caused by Hib.
</P>
<P>
About 5 percent of children with bacterial meningitis due to
Hib die of the illness, while 15 percent to 30 percent suffer from
mental retardation or deafness.
</P>
<P>
CDCP stressed the continued need for widespread and aggressive
immunization efforts and continued surveillance of Hib invasive
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
