<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Slams Europe Parliament over Kurdish Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey accused the European
Parliament (EP) on Friday of attempting to internationalize the
Kurdish issue, which Ankara considers an internal affair.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, the Turkish Foreign Ministry
criticized the EP, the consultative body of the European Union
(EU), of calling for the convening of an international conference
on the Kurdish issue in a report adopted on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement termed the EP move as "interfering in Turkey's
political and social systems as well as foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
It is far from "constructive and realistic" and will harm the
Turkey-EU relations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK), was detained by Italian police upon his arrival aboard a
Russian Airlines passenger plane from Moscow on November 12.
</P>
<P>
Italy rejected a Turkish warrant for the extradition of the
Kurdish rebel chief, citing its constitution forbids extradition
to a country that the suspect may face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said that
he backed the EU initiative to try Ocalan before an international
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The PKK took up arms in 1984 for self rule in Turkey's
mainly-Kurdish southeast and over 37,000 people, including PKK
rebels, government troops and civilians, have been killed in the
conflicts since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
