<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Breweries to Move Primary Listing to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South African Breweries
(SAB), the world's fourth largest brewer, plan to transfer its
primary listing from the Johannesburg Stock Exchange (JSE) to the
London Stock Exchange next year.
</P>
<P>
The company said Friday that it would transfer its core
operations, beverage gaming and hotel businesses, into a new
company that will list in London by March, South African
newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
SAB's decision to leave its country of birth follows fast on
the heels of announcement by Anglo American group, the mining
giant and the biggest listed company in South Africa, that it
would transfer its primary listing to London.
</P>
<P>
With SAB's move, six of the top 10 companies on the JSE will
now have their primary listing in London.
</P>
<P>
The other five are Anglo, the largest, Richemont, Anglogold,
Billiton and Minorco, most of which shifted their primary
listings overseas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The SAB share price closed 200c firmer at 91 Rand (15.6 U.S.
Dollars) Friday following the release of the news. At 91 Rand,
the group has a market capitalization of around 33 billion Rand
(5.64 billion Dollars), which places it fourth in the terms of
size on the JSE.
</P>
<P>
In common with Anglo, SAB cited a desire to get cheaper access
to capital to fund further significant international growth. The
move, the group said, would enable it to compete on the world
stage with its major international partners.
</P>
<P>
SAB, the first industrial company to be listed on the JSE in
1897, said the newly formed company, SAB Plc, would have its
secondary listing in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
At its present market capitalization, SAB would rank at around
70 on the FTSE-100 index of Britain's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
"SAB Plc will be one of the world's largest brewers in terms
of volume of sales, with approximately 25 million hectoliters
sold in South Africa and a further 18 million hectoliters
internationally in the year ended March 1998," it said.
</P>
<P>
The group said the new structure would allow it to accelerate
international expansion in a rapidly consolidating beverage
market, while continuing to strengthen its existing operations in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It also might take the opportunity offered by the London Stock
Exchange listing to raise additional equity finance, SAB said.
</P>
</TEXT>
