<HEADLINE> Zambian Inter-Party Talks Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian inter-party talks has
made initiative progress on contentious issues concerning
elections, government-owned Times of Zambia said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the 11-hour meeting chaired by President Frederick Chiluba
in Lusaka Friday, 22 political party presidents agreed to uproot
Nikuv, an Israeli company contracted to deal with voters cards
and registers.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties have been accusing the company of
practising fraud in favor of the ruling party during the
country's 1996 general and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The party presidents resolved not to renew the Nikuv at the
end of this year when the local government elections were due.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition parties failed to press for
postponement of the local government elections scheduled for
December 30.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, a committee of eight party presidents was set
up to continue ironing out the remaining issues regarding
constitutional changes and electoral process which have been
hindering the country's political process in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Any four members of the committee can form a quorum to hold
meetings with President Chiluba, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
When opening the talks which were abandoned in 1992, Chiluba,
who is also leader of the ruling party but was seen as a
"neutral" person to chair the talks, urged all the political
parties to try to create a political culture of dialog so that
they could resolve the country's problems through concerted
efforts.
</P>
<P>
The inter-party talks attracted 22 political parties including
the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) and the
largest opposition party, the United National Independence Party
(UNIP) led by former president Kenneth Kaunda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
