<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Mulam: Better Educated Ethnic Group (1) (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: The following is
the sixth of a series of stories on the rapidly-changing lives and
culture of the Zhuang, Miao, Yao, Maonan, Gin, and 6 other ethnic
groups living in China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, which
will have its 40th anniversary on December 11:
</P>
<P>
Among China's 1.2 billion people, the 200,000 members of the
Mulam ethnic group are little known.
</P>
<P>
Mo Hongsheng, magistrate of the Luocheng Mulam Autonomous
County government in Guangxi, says that although the Mulam ethnic
group is smaller in population, their level of education is no
less than that of the Han Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The Mulam ranks second among China's 55 ethnic minorities,
after the Korean people, in terms of education and have many
writers, artists, scientists, and educators.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Chengyi, who got her doctor degree in biochemistry from
the City University of New York this year, is the first Mulam
woman to earn a doctorate abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Senior Middle School in the Luocheng Autonomous County is
a source of many educated people. The first generation of Mulam
university students got their education at this school, which was
founded in 1938. Its graduates are spread over many parts of China
and in foreign countries, one of the farthest away being in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The school has a row of modern buildings and well-trimmed
lawns, even lovelier than some universities. The school is
equipped with more than 50 computers, and every classroom has a
television set.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jiuquan, the school's Party Secretary, says that every
national minority has its own strong points and studying hard is a
fine tradition of the Mulam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Mulam: Better Educated Ethnic Group (2) (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Mulam are an aboriginal people of southern China. In
Luocheng County, stone axes dating back 6,000 years have been
found. During the Song (960-1279) and Yuan (1271-1368) dynasties,
the Mulam maintained features of their matriarchal society.
</P>
<P>
They are quite different from other ethnic groups in Guangxi,
most of whom live in mountainous areas. The Mulam later came to
control the county seat on the plains where transport was easier.
They have more contacts with the outside world and understand the
importance of learning far better.
</P>
<P>
In the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties,
academies of classical learning and old-style private schools in
the Mulam communities were quite popular, and many people sought
official posts by taking part in the imperial examinations.
</P>
<P>
For the past several years, China has been pushing its strategy
of improving China through science and education, which is in line
with the Mulam group's thoughts. The county government has paid
even greater attention to education.
</P>
<P>
According to the county magistrate, Mo Hongsheng, the county has
established an education fund to finance construction of schools
and aid students from impoverished families.
</P>
<P>
If a national minority group wants to become stronger, it can't
only depend on the Central Government for finances, the most
important thing is to improve its culture and the quality of the
people, Mo says. He's a college graduate who recently passed exams
for advanced university studies.
</P>
<P>
Many ethnic people who are more poorly educated than the Han, a
persistent problem among an overwhelming majority of the ethnic
groups, lack qualified personnel to compete in the market economy.
</P>
<P>
But, the autonomous county has nine-year compulsory education
which has helped improve the culture of the Mulam. Farmers, for
example, have used their new knowledge and technology to improve
pig breeding.
</P>
<P>
The Mulam group's modern education includes putonghua, or
Mandarin Chinese, in middle schools, and Chinese versions of
Chinese and foreign literary classics can be found in local
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
An effort has also been made to preserve the culture and
traditions of the Mulam and the county government has decided to
revive the Yifan festival, a sort of songfest, this year.
Recently, some Mulam people even created their own opera in the
Mulam language.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An Israeli Soldier Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 5 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli soldier was wounded
in a Lebanese guerrilla attack in south Lebanon Friday night, the
Orient radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The casualty came when guerrillas of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, launched an offensive with heavy guns
and grenades against an Israeli post in al-Aishi, on the eastern
edge of the Israeli occupied zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli radio Saturday morning confirmed the injury, saying
its warplanes in response blasted Lebanon's southern town of
Nabatieh, believed to be a hideout for Hezbollah guerrillas just
north of its self-styled security zone.
</P>
<P>
This was the latest Israeli casualty since seven of its
soldiers were killed in a spate of Hezbollah bombing attacks in 10
days last month. A total of 23 Israeli soldiers have lost their
lives in south Lebanon since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
The growing heavy losses have rekindled a heated debate in
Israel over its continued military presence in the area it
occupied in 1985 after two invasions.
</P>
<P>
The popular call for a unilateral withdrawal from Lebanon is
growing louder, but Israeli cabinet, after a number of meetings,
still insisted on its security conditions for a pullout.
</P>
<P>
In April, Israeli cabinet offered to withdrawal from south
Lebanon but conditioned the implementation of the U.N. Resolution
425 on Lebanese government's arrangement to guarantee security of
Israel's north.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria flatly rejected the proposal,
demanding Israel leave the country without any preconditions as
stipulated by the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north
from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's resistance spearheaded by Hezbollah has since been
fighting to oust Israeli forces and its proxy South Lebanon Army
militia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
