<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh on Long Road to Prosperity (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- As one of the world's least
developed countries, Bangladesh has made relentless efforts to
develop its economy in recent years, but the efforts have been
largely offset by protracted political uncertainty and frequent
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
A few years ago, when natural gas was first discovered
underneath Bangladesh, the poverty-stricken Bangladeshis were
overjoyed and described the country as "floating on gas." Both
government officials and ordinary people pinned their hopes on
getting rid of poverty through gas exploitation.
</P>
<P>
The excitement, however, didn't last long. In accordance with
the production-sharing contracts already signed with foreign oil
and gas companies, Bangladesh would get only 25 percent of the
extracted gas, and would have to procure the rest 75 percent from
the foreign companies at international prices, which were much
higher than that of local-company-produced gas.
</P>
<P>
When the first foreign company-drilled gas well began to
produce gas this year, the government found it in a difficult
situation, as it would neither have enough money to buy large
quantity of gas if all the wells operated by foreign companies
were in production nor have the capacity to consume the gas.
</P>
<P>
This problem does not end there. According to latest official
statistics, Bangladesh has a gas reserve of 23 trillion cubic
feet, which can only meet the demand for gas at the present rate
of consumption till the year of 2015. There is simply no
possibility for Bangladesh to export gas, as it can not meet its
own domestic demand in the long run, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998 witnessed the worst flood hitting Bangladesh in
100 years, in which half of the country's 127 million population
were affected, and large stretches of crops destroyed and
infrastructure facilities severely damaged, dealing a heavy blow
to its economy.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates put the total loss at around 4.3 billion
U.S. dollars, about 10 percent of the South Asian nation's gross
domestic product. The agriculture sector alone suffered a huge
loss of about 72.5 billion taka (1.49 billion dollars), according
to Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
"Only the damage of crops by the flood caused a loss of 36.74
billion taka (756 million dollars)," she said. Over 740,000
million hectares of land were damaged in the prolonged flooding
between July and September.
</P>
<P>
The flood resulted in a food shortage of about 4 million tons,
nearly one fifth of the country's annual food requirement, and
observers here are afraid of a silent famine in Bangladesh in the
coming months, particularly in the winter months between November
and March.
</P>
<P>
To fund its short- and long-term post-flood rehabilitation
programs of over 941 million dollars for the current fiscal year
starting from July 1998, the government has appealed for
international assistance and mobilized domestic resources. For
this end, an international aid of 230 million dollars and local
resource requirements of over 600 million dollars would be needed,
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh on Long Road to Prosperity (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But to get international assistance and mobilize domestic
resources is not an easy job. Even if the government could get
what it needed, the implementation of the rehabilitation programs
is still a problem, observers here said. The opposition has
already accused the ruling party of being indifferent to
rehabilitation of flood-affected people, as the "genuinely
affected people were not getting relief and relief materials were
misappropriated by the ruling party leaders."
</P>
<P>
It takes time for the country to recover from calamities. A
severe flood struck Bangladesh in 1988, and it was not until 1997
that the country had fully recovered from the disaster, according
to experts.
</P>
<P>
It would take a much longer period of time for the country to
recover from this year's flood with regard to its duration and
magnitude and considering the volatile political situation in the
country, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Political parties in Bangladesh have a liking for calling
hartals, according to the observers. During the five-year rule of
the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) between 1991 and 1996, the
then opposition Bangladesh Awami League (BAL) organized 173 days
of hartals, and after the BAL came to power in 1996, the
opposition BNP has also called hartals one after another.
</P>
<P>
One day's hartal in Bangladesh would cause a loss of 3.86
billion taka (84.4 million dollars), according to Finance Minister
Shah A.M.S. Kibria.
</P>
<P>
A three-day hartal organized by the seven-party opposition
alliance in early November this year put all economic activities
in the country at a standstill, and right after the hartal, the
ruling BAL announced unilateral renunciation of hartal in the
country "in the greater interest of economic development of the
country."
</P>
<P>
But the major opposition BNP rejected the government's
"no-hartal" call, and its Chairperson Kaleda Zia called upon the
people to take vow afresh to hasten the fall of the present
government "at any cost," accusing the government of failing to
maintain law and order in the country and being indifferent to
rehabilitation of flood-affected people.
</P>
<P>
Scarcity of natural resources, frequent natural disasters and a
large population might be partially responsible for the country's
economic underdevelopment, but unstable political situation was
the key obstacle to the development of Bangladesh, with more than
half of its 127-million population still living below the poverty
line on an area of just over 144,000 square kilometers, the
observers said.
</P>
<P>
Only when the political parties sit down and settle their
disputes through dialogue and discussion instead of taking to the
streets to lodge their protests, can the country be able to
eventually get rid of poverty and move towards prosperity, the
observers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Urges to Have Debt Burden Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Donors have been urged to help
Kenya reduce debt burden which local business people say is so
heavy as to constitute a great impediment to the country's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
This east African country spends a staggering 48 billion
Shillings (800 million U.S. Dollars) annually in debts repayment,
the East African Standard newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Unless the debts are written off, Kenya will suffer from
further economic deterioration, the report quoted Jubilee 2000
Coalition Director Ann Pettifor as saying. The coalition groups
prominent Asian-origin business people across the country.
</P>
<P>
Kenya currently has a foreign debt of 294 billion Shillings
(4.9 billion Dollars) with 240 billion Shillings (four billion
Dollars) accrued in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Pettifor said the conditions for debt cancellation should be
decided by independent international arbitration to save the
common Kenyans from starvation while the government service
debts.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), she
criticized, were applying double standards to African countries
by giving them loans while interest earned on the loans was what
was sustaining the two institutions.
</P>
<P>
Pettifor noted that there is no bankruptcy law, and sovereign
governments cannot go bankrupt, saying, "so when a country is
unable to repay its loans it goes back to the IMF for another
loan to pay old loans accompanied by tough IMF economic
conditions."
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended the key 205-million-Dollar loan package to
Kenya in mid 1997, citing poor governance and rampant corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
