<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wine Can Reduce Stroke Risk, Study Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 4 (Xinhua) -- People who drink moderate
amounts of wine have a lower risk of stroke than those who drink
beer or spirits, according to the latest Friday issue of Stroke, a
publication of the American Heart Institution.
</P>
<P>
The result was based on a 16-year study of more than 13,000
people conducted by Dr. Thomas Truelson and his colleagues at the
Institute of Preventive Medicine in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
Acoording to the study, those who said they drank between one
and six glasses of wine a week had a 34 percent lower risk of
stroke than those who said they never drank wine or hardly ever
drank it.
</P>
<P>
Daily wine drinkers had a 32 percent lower risk, while those
who drank beer or spirits showed no significantly lower risk.
</P>
<P>
Wine, especially red wine, contains healthy plant compounds
like tannins, flavonoids and polyphenols, which can act as
antioxidants and help stop fat from sticking to artery walls and
clogging them up.
</P>
<P>
The American Heart Association, however, stressed that
excessive drinking of wine can cause heart disease and
cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
