<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 43 People Charged in Drug Network in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Forty-three people,
including 13 corrections officers, were charged with operating an
intricate drug-dealing network led by a jailed dealer in Florida
State of the United States, police sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The charges follow a secret investigation launched a year ago
involving local, state and federal agencies. The probe found that
officers allegedly looked the other way or actively took part as
marijuana, cocaine and other contraband was smuggled into jails
for inmates in exchange for cash, jewelry, car repairs and
sporting equipment.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. attorney's office unsealed an indictment Friday
charging 26 people, including Eduardo Manzano, the alleged leader
of a jailhouse cocaine and marijuana distribution organization.
Manzano made payments to corrections officers at the detention
center and at the correctional center to gain access to phones,
drugs, food and clothing, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
The state attorney's office arrested and charged 17 more
people, who will be indicted during the next few weeks, the
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
