<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Emergency Remains in Mexico City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Mexico City remained in
phase one of environment emergency for the second day in a row,
because of serious air pollution, the city's Environment
Secretariat told the press Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mexico City's Metropolitan Air Quality Index (Imeca) for ozone
content has passed the 200-point level, according to the
secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican capital authorities said the main reason for the
pollution is that, with little wind, contaminant substances in the
air cannot disperse. On Friday afternoon, the ozone level in the
air reached 218 points.
</P>
<P>
Because of the phase one emergency, 50 percent of the almost 3
million motor vehicles in the city have been kept off the road,
according to the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, phase one was enforced in May when the Imeca
for ozone surpasses 240 points, as occurred Thursday when it
reached 262.
</P>
<P>
The measure is suspended after the ozone contamination level
drops under 180 points. Phase two is decreed when it surpasses 350.
</P>
<P>
During Phase two environmental emergency, not only motor
vehicles are affected, 20 percent of the gas stations in the city
and factories with pollutant emissions will be closed, and outdoor
school and other cultural and sports activities cancelled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
