<HEADLINE> S. Korea Fields in Pro Baseballers for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has scored a major
coup over rivals Japan and Chinese Taipei in getting Los Angeles
Dodgers pitcher Park Chan-ho back for the baseball competition in
the 13th Asian Games to be started on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will use professionals at the Games for the first
time, while Japan failed to get the release of the New York Mets'
Hideo Nomo.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei has got Kuo Li-jiang back from the Hanshin
Tigers in Japan but the team does not have enough professionals to
compete and seems set to be left licking their wounds.
</P>
<P>
Park has become South Korea's top male athlete with his success
at the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
Despite his superstar status, the 25-year-old ace pitcher has
overcome doubts about how he will get on with other members of the
squad and insists it is a "great honour" to play for his country.
