<HEADLINE> Value of Construction Activity in New Zealand Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The value of construction
activity within New Zealand fell in the third quarter this year,
according to New Zealand's Deputy Government Statistician Ian
Ewing.
</P>
<P>
In a media release issued here Saturday, he said it is
estimated that a total of 1,517.4 million NZ dollars (804.2
million U.S. dollars) of construction work was put in place in the
third quarter, 17.6 percent less than that put in place in the
previous third quarter.
</P>
<P>
"The total value of construction work has fallen steadily since
the September quarter last year, in line with the decline
recorded in building consents issued over that time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ewing said the majority of the decline in construction activity
was recorded in residential construction, with work put in place
in the third quarter this year being 873 million NZ dollars (463
million U.S. dollars) or 21.9 percent less than the same quarter
of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
