<HEADLINE> New Zealand Revises Export Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Statistics New Zealand has
revised
the country's trade deficit for the year to June 1998 from 841
million NZ
dollars (445.7 million U.S. dollars) to 599 million NZ dollars
(317.5
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a media release issued Saturday, Government Statistician Len
Cook
said the revisions are largely due to late export entries received
by the
New Zealand Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
The value of exports for the year to June 1998 has been revised

upwards from 21,748 million NZ dollars (11,526 million U.S.
dollars) to
21,990 million NZ dollars (11,655 million NZ dollars). The revised
figure
recorded a 4.5 percent increase when compared to the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
These revisions have resulted in an improvement to the balance
of
trade for the year to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
A joint education campaign undertaken by Statistics New Zealand
and
the New Zealand Customs Service has stimulated exporters holding
on to
export entries to send them in to Customs in order to improve the
timeliness of export documentation, Cook said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
