<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Issues Fuel Pump Alert on Airbus Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA) on Friday ordered the inspection and
repair of fuel pumps on some Airbus aircraft, one day after
issuing an order on Boeing 747 fuel pumps.
</P>
<P>
The FAA asked for inspection and repair of center fuel tank
pumps on the Airbus A300 because of fears they could ignite fuel
fumes.
</P>
<P>
FAA's action follows action last week by the French
airworthiness authority Direction General de l'Aviation Civile
(DGAC).
</P>
<P>
The FAA said in a statement that there were 67 of the
twin-engine wide-body A300-600 series aircraft in operation with
U.S. carriers that included American Airlines and Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
Fuel tank ignition sources have received great attention by the
FAA since the 1996 crash of an Boeing 747 into the ocean off New
York that killed all 230 people on board when its central fuel
tank exploded. The exact cause of that blast has not been
identified.
</P>
<P>
The FAA ordered airlines flying Boeing 747s on Thursday to
change the way they manage fuel to prevent dry running of pumps
while a newly discovered problem with pump bearings was resolved.
</P>
<P>
The FAA asked operators to leave enough fuel in the center tank
of all 747 models and cease using the horizontal stabilizer tank
in the rear of the 747-400 to prevent pumps overheating while the
premature wear of bearings was probed.
</P>
<P>
Airbus is a consortium made up of Dasa, which is a unit of
DaimlerChrysler AG, British Aerospace Plc, state-owned
Aerospatiale of France and Spain's Construcciones Aeronauticas SA
(Casa). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
