<HEADLINE> Laid-off Workers Encouraged to Start Private Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Workers, laid off as a result of
the economic structural reform, will receive one-time grant aid
worth 1 million leva to open their own business, the cabinet
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision replaced an earlier provision, under which this
amount was meant as a loan.
</P>
<P>
However, if the grantees disburse the aid for other purposes,
they will have to repay it, with no interest charged, said Social
Minister Ivan Neikov.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers will be entitled to the grant after the new
ordinance comes into force. They should apply for the grant within
three months after their employer lays them off.
</P>
<P>
The funds are expected to come from the national budget after
jobless workers sign a contract with an employment office.
</P>
<P>
Neikov said he expects that more than 30 percent of the workers
entitled to the fund will set up joint businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Thursday decision was adopted following broad discussions
and consultations with the social partners and the banking
circles, Neikov said.
</P>
<P>
The idea is that laid-off workers receive the grant promptly
and encounter the minimum possible bureaucratic hindrance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Pakistan Agree to Settle F-16 Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Pakistan have agreed to settle their dispute over an aborted sale
of U.S. F-16 fighters to Pakistan, a U.S.-Pakistan joint statement
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement, issued by the White House, reported on the
meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Sharif "emphasized the need for a
fair and early resolution of the F-16 issue," and Clinton
"reaffirmed his commitment to such a resolution."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan paid 658 million U.S. dollars for the purchase of 28
F-16 fighters in the 1980s, but has never received the aircraft
because of U.S. sanctions imposed in 1990 for Pakistani nuclear
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting at the White House, President Clinton
briefed Prime Minister Sharif on what he called U.S. efforts to
compensate for the aborted purchase.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the United States has already paid 157
million dollars back to Islamabad, raising the money by selling
aircraft components to other countries.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand on Tuesday agreed to pay some 105 million dollars
over 10 years to lease the fighters, providing additional funds
that could be used to give Pakistan some of its money back.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. officials said they were still waiting for official
notification of the New Zealand's offer.
</P>
<P>
They said the United States had given Pakistan its ideas on how
to resolve the issue of the aborted war plane sale and Pakistan
was evaluating them.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement also said Sharif reiterated his invitation
to Clinton to visit Pakistan. Clinton said he hoped it would be
possible to visit Pakistan next year. Clinton had planned to
visit India and Pakistan this year, but the planned trip was
canceled because of the two countries' tit-for-tat nuclear test
explosions in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
