<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Gang Leader Executed (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Cheung Tze-keung, leader of a
36-member gang which committed a series of felonies in inland
China and Hong Kong, was executed today in Guangzhou in line with
a last instance verdict issued by the Higher People's Court of
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Chan Chi-ho, Ma Shangzhong, Liang Hui and Chin Hon-sau, members
of Cheung's gang, were also executed in line with court verdicts.
</P>
<P>
Cheung and his accomplices were charged with a number of crimes
ranging from illegally buying and selling and transporting
explosives, guns and ammunition to smuggling firearms and
ammunition, kidnaping, robbery and concealing stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate People's Court of Guangzhou, the capital of
Guangdong, announced the first instance verdict in Cheung's case
on November 12. The court sentenced the five coconspirators to
death, with the permanent deprivation of political rights. Chu
Yuk-sing and Li Wan were sentenced to death with a two-year
suspension, and the remaining 29 defendants received prison terms
up to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Cheung and 28 defendants appealed the first instance verdict
with the Higher People's Court of Guangdong Province and requested
lesser punishment.
</P>
<P>
The five-member collegiate bench formed to review the case
examined all related files, questioned the 29 appellants and seven
first instance defendants in the case, heard arguments by defense
lawyers and carefully scrutinized all criminal facts and laws
applicable to first instance verdict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
