<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Demands UNITA Set Free U.N. Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Friday evening demanded that Angola's rebel UNITA
immediately release 14 U.N. peacekeepers from two towns where
fighting has intensified.
</P>
<P>
The demand came at the end of an emergent closed-door meeting
held late on Friday by the 15-member Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council demands that UNITA permit the immediate
and unconditional departure of MONUA (the U.N. Observer Mission in
Angola) personnel from Andulo and Bailundo," the council said in a
press statement after closed-door consultations. UNITA is the
short form for the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Security Council for the month of
December, Jassim Mohammed Buallay of Bahrain, said the council
held UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi "personally responsible for their
safety."
</P>
<P>
Ten of the soldiers are from India, all of them in Andulo.
Others are from Senegal, Sweden and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government forces bombed the Andulo area at midday
on Friday (local time), giving rise to fears the peacekeepers, who
are almost hostages, would be endangered.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council deplores the deterioration of the
situation in Angola and urges there be no further hostilities,"
the council president said, adding that UNITA was primarily
responsible for an impasse in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The emergent council meeting was partially prompted by a letter
from Savimbi, who said that he felt "that the presence of MONUA in
Andulo and Bailundo is important before and during the full
implementation of the remaining tasks of the Lusaka Protocol," a
peace accord signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who is
on a North Africa visit, issued a statement via his spokesman's
office here, saying that the United Nations had decided to
relocate the peacekeepers a month ago.
</P>
<P>
But the leadership of UNITA "under various pretexts," had
refused to provide clearance for U.N. planes to land to evacuate
the U.N. personnel, Annan said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Of late, Annan said in his report to the Security Council that
peace agreements, including the Lusaka Protocol, have not been
well honored.
</P>
<P>
MONUA, which currently groups 1,016 observers, has been in
Angola since June 30, 1997 to help implement the Lusaka Protocol
designed to end nearly two decades of civil war between the
Angolan Government and UNITA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
