<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central American Leaders to Ask U.S. to Extend Work Permits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN SALVADOR, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Central American
presidents will urge the United States for an 18-month extension
of the work permit for illegal immigrants from the region,
Salvadoran President Armando Calderon Sol said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Central American countries will travel next week
to Washington to attend the opening of the Consultative Group
called by the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) to obtain
donations for the reconstruction of the countries ravaged by
hurricane Mitch in November.
</P>
<P>
The presidents will take advantage of the meeting to visit
U.S. congressmen and other political leaders to advocate for the
immigrants, whose money remittances mean a big resource for
Central American economies.
</P>
<P>
If the United States agrees to extend the temporary permits,
"we would have time to lobby for definitive status," and in those
18 months "we would have to direct our efforts to the Congress...
to create conscience in the U.S. public sector," Calderon Sol said.
</P>
<P>
Following the disasters caused by hurricane Mitch, the U.S.
authorities announced a suspension of deporting Central Americans
who had not obtained migratory status, but deportation could be
resumed soon.
</P>
<P>
Calderon Sol said that his colleagues have planned "a joint
strategy" to help the immigrants obtain a migratory status.
</P>
</TEXT>
