<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's King Calls For Unity in Face of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai King Bhumibol Adulyadej
called on the Thai people to be united in overcoming the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The King gave this message to the Thais on the eve of his
birthday Friday in a speech on one of the toughest years in the
country's history.
</P>
<P>
"Bringing happiness or prosperity to a nation is not the work
of one group. We need to cooperate, using specific skills or
knowledge that one has," the king said in remarks published by
Saturday's Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"People who have the same skills or knowledge need to work
together, and when they disagree on anything, they should discuss
their conflicts rather than quarrel," the king said.
</P>
<P>
He said quarreling is dictated by emotions while discussion
requires wisdom. Only when people use their wisdom will they be
able to find out solutions to their problems.
</P>
<P>
Clarifying his advice about "self-sufficiency" which he gave
when the financial crisis broke out last year, the king explained
that he had not called for a "cave age" style of living.
</P>
<P>
He said people misinterpreted his statement that it would be
satisfactory if just one-fourth of the self-sufficiency ideology
can be implemented.
</P>
<P>
"I was not calling for implementation of a self-sufficient
economy in one-fourth of Thailand's total area. I need to bring
this up because even academics did not quite get it. Maybe I was
not that clear the last time, but from what I wrote it was quite
obvious that I was referring to action, not land space," the
monarch said.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to do it in its totality, for that would mean
going back to the stone age, the time when people lived in caves.
</P>
<P>
"People in those days needed to rely on themselves because
other tribes were all enemies. They fought and never cooperated,
so each group needed self-sufficiency," the king said.
</P>
<P>
"Today we see that we can rely on just around 25 percent of
ourselves. We can see the fruits of what we do are mostly traded
with other necessities. That is why I came up with the one-fourth
figure," he said.
</P>
<P>
The king's address took place against the background of
political storms surrounding the government, whose latest
legislative package to revitalize the economy has stirred up
considerable xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand still has gold, but some types of gold have been
overlooked, and foreigners pack what we discard. We are a happy
country without foreigners coming to dig (gold) and even if they
do come, they will dig for us as well," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
