<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Small, Medium Enterprises Get Support Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai industry and finance
ministries approved a 40-billion-baht (1.1 billion U.S. dollars)
fund to assist small and medium-sized enterprises next year.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Industry Ministry confirmed Saturday that
the fund will come from six state-owned financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The fund is in line with the government's policy to promote
small and medium enterprises (SMEs) so that they will become the
engine of an economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The industry and finance ministries also agreed to improve the
efficiency of the Small Industrial Finance Corporation and the
Small Industrial Credit Management Corporation, hoping the two
could be upgraded into state enterprises in the future.
</P>
<P>
SMEs, which do not have non-performing loans (NPLs) or which
are in need of re-financing, would be given first priority in
getting loans from the six state-owned financial houses.
</P>
<P>
For SMEs which have NPLs, the industries could also apply for
loans but they would have to first restructure their debts with
their creditors.
</P>
<P>
Of the 40 billion baht fund, 2 billion baht (55.6 million
dollars) are from the Industrial Finance Corporation of Thailand;
3 billion (83.3 million dollars) from the Small Industrial Finance
Corporation; 2 billion (55.6 million baht) from the Bank of
Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives; 1 billion (27.8 million
dollars) from the Government Savings Bank; 5 billion (138.9
million dollars) from the Exim Bank; and the rest from the Bank of
Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
