<HEADLINE> Foreign Students Hone Language Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The freezing cold of winter
here has not dampened foreign students' enthusiasm for learning
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday evening, 300 students from 50 countries took part in
a performance featuring Chinese language artistic programs and
singing and dancing from their native countries, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The performance, organized by the Ministry of Education and
Beijing municipal government in the Century Theater, attracted
officials from the ministries of education, culture and foreign
affairs, 200 foreign diplomats from 78 embassies and 1,200
foreigners studying in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Foreign students have seized opportunities like this in the
past few years to practise their Chinese-language skills, sources
from the Ministry of Education said.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry's Department for International
Co-operation and Exchanges, China has received 258,000 foreign
students since the reform and opening-up polices were introduced
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The number is increasing at an average of 30 percent a year,
despite the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry's latest statistics indicate that last year,
43,712 students from 160 countries were studying in 335 colleges
and universities throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Some 76.87 percent of the students came from Asia, 9.85 percent
from Europe and the rest from America, Africa and Oceania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
