<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta Governor Backs Shooting of Street Thugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- As Jakarta's crime rate
continues to soar, Governor Sutiyoso has given support to the
decision of police to "shoot to immobilize" in their campaign to
quell civil disobedience, the Indonesian Observer reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"That's the right action. I support such stern action in
immobilizing robbers because the city's crime rate has now gone
beyond the limit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The governor admitted that Jakarta's international image has
been severely tarnished by the recent spate of car-jacking and
toll road robberies, especially because many of the victims have
been foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"It seems like we're living in the middle of a jungle because
so many people have very boldly defied the law. We must not let
this sort of condition continue indefinitely. Therefore, we have
to stop the criminals," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta police spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Edward Aritonang
told reporters that from November 25 to December 2, police shot
five alleged criminals, three of whom perished, and arrested
nearly 70 others for their involvement in street crimes.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of areas in the city regarded as "hot spots"
for crime has soared. In July there were only 31 hot spots. But
the number rose to 50 in September and now stands at 60, with many
of the danger areas at toll roads.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Jakarta legislative assembly have expressed
grave concern over the increasing number of unsafe places in the
city.
</P>
<P>
Head of the military faction in the assembly Sumekar K.W. said
the number of police in Jakarta must be increased, or failing
that, civilian guards should assist with security measures.
