<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Helpful to Policy Making for Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior UN Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) official said that China's First
National Agricultural Census, to be completed in 1999, will help
the country draw policies for its agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
"The information will provide a sound base for the planning and
development of this key sector of the economy and thus contribute
to alimentary security and stability for China's population as
well as for the world," today's China Daily quoted Hartwig Haen,
FAO's assistant director-general, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 11-year-long census, the largest and most complex of its
kind the world has ever witnessed, and co-organized by China, FAO,
and Italy, released a first set of results Friday from
computerized data processing.
</P>
<P>
The first manually tabulated results of the agricultural census
showed that 561 million people are economically active in rural
areas and of those, 424 million are involved in agriculture.
These numbers differ from former statistics, which spoke of 453
million people working in the rural sector.
</P>
<P>
Another important revelation from the census is that the
cropped area is greater than expected, despite the ongoing loss
of arable land to industrial development and the building of
infrastructure, roads, airports and housing.
</P>
<P>
"Final data from the census will shed light on the use of
fertilizers. The data will also indicate whether China has reached
its productive potential in terms of food development," said Haen.
</P>
<P>
The census collected information on land use, crop areas,
livestock, agricultural employment and other related issues. Over
200 million rural households were visited and interviewed by more
than 7 million census representatives, all in only a few weeks in
last January.
</P>
<P>
"China's agricultural statistics system will be further
improved with the completion of the first agricultural census,"
said Liu Hong, director-general of the National Bureau of
Statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
