<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission to be Created to Demark Peru-Ecuador Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori Friday announced that a joint commission will soon be
established for placing markers along the country's border with
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The joint demarcation commission, to be set up on December 11
in Tumes, north Peru, will be made up of the delegations appointed
by the Peruvian and Ecuadoran governments, said Fujimori in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said last Monday that the demarcation process on the
Peruvian-Ecuadoran common border would be carried out in three
stages -- agreement on where to put the border markers by the two
countries, removal of land mines around the marker sites and the
actual placement of markers.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador signed a peace treaty in Brasilia in October
to end a dispute over a 78-kilometer section of their border in
the Andean foothils in the Amazon jungle.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the disputed section of the border will
follow the heights of teh Cordillera del Condor ountain range, as
Peru had claimed.
</P>
<P>
But a one-square-kilometer hilly area within Peru's territory
called Tiwintza will be granted to Ecuador as private property,
with Peru maintaing sovereignty over it.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador fought wars in 1941, 1981 and 1995 over the
disputed region. Peace talks over the dispute began in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
