<HEADLINE> Sino-Global Technology Exchanges Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- More than a decade ago,
scientific circles in developed counties were hesitant to
co-operate with their Chinese counterparts because of China's
relatively backward technology.
</P>
<P>
Today developed countries and international organizations are
actively expanding collaboration with China thanks to its rapid
economic and social development, a representative from the
Ministry of Science and Technology was quoted as saying by China
Daily today.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-European project for modernized flood monotoring
systems, which started in 1991 along the Fuchunjiang River in
Zhejiang province, has played a significant role in flood
forecasts and helped save about one billion yuan, said Wang
Shaoqi, director of the ministry's department for international
co-operation, at a conference yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held to mark the 20th anniversary of China's
scientific and technological reforms and development.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department for Basic Science Research, the
State will invest two billion yuan to gain technological
breakthroughs in fields such as large scale scientific calculation
and genetic engineering projects.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will reinforce theoretical research to help
develop the agriculture, energy, information science, natural
resources, environment, and population and health sectors, said
its Secretary-General Lin Quan.
</P>
<P>
"When China began to implement its reform and opening-up
policies in 1978, rural and social development plans focused
mainly on meeting the demands of people's basic living
conditions. Then the plans gradually shifted to improving the
people's life and seeking sustainable development, "said Liu
Yanhua, director of the ministry's Department for Rural and Social
Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
