<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Customs Expands Anti-Smuggling Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in Shanghai,
China's leading industrial city, have handled 226 smuggling cases
involving some 307 million yuan (36 million U.S. dollars) over the
past four months.
</P>
<P>
China launched a nationwide anti-smuggling campaign in July
this year following a related national conference.
</P>
<P>
Local customs officers have confiscated motor vehicles,
chemical raw materials, cigarettes and telecommunications
equipment in over a dozen raids carried out since July.
</P>
<P>
The customs department has strengthened supervision of both
imports and exports of chemicals used to make drugs and various
other strategic goods.
</P>
<P>
The department also established hot lines to accept tips
related to smuggled goods.
</P>
<P>
Numerous industries, including the chemical and textile raw
materials, refined oil products and computer sectors, have
rebounded since introduction of the anti-smuggling campaign.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is in the process of establishing a special
anti-smuggling police unite which will become fully operational on
January 1 next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
