<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Attorney General Summons Former President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Attorney General
Andi Ghalib Friday said he had already sent a summons to former
president Soeharto for questioning about the corrupt, collusive
and nepotistic practices he is believed to have engaged in while
in power.
</P>
<P>
"I send the summons directly to Cendana (the home of the former
president) this afternoon," he was quoted by national newspapers
Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although Ghalib did not specify the exact date of the summons,
the Criminal Code states that a summons must be issued three days
prior to the designated day.
</P>
<P>
Thus if the letter issued on December 4, the former president
would be required to attend Attorney General's Office on Monday
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie on Thursday ordered Ghalib to speed up
the investigation into Soeharto's alleged ill-gotten wealth,
dropping plans to set up an independent team to probe the former
president's wealth.
</P>
<P>
The president also issued a decree empowering Ghalib to act
more decisively.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib said he has appointed Antonius Sujata, junior attorney
for special crime cases, as head of the questioning team.
</P>
<P>
He said the team is also set to summon former ministers and
other high-ranking officials in a bid to find evidence of corrupt,
collusive and nepotistic practices during Soeharto's 32 years in
power.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether he had enough evidence to place Soeharto
under house arrest, Ghalib said: "We must be very careful. It's a
big and interesting affairs."
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tanjung Friday told reporters
that Ghalib could put Soeharto under house arrest if it was deemed
necessary.
</P>
<P>
The move drew a swift response from Soeharto, who said that he
was ready to face any probe into his wealth as well as allegations
of corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices.
</P>
<P>
In the first public comments by Soeharto since students stepped
up their pressure on the government to open the inquiry into his
alleged wealth a few months ago, Soeharto said he was not above
the law.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a challenge. I realize that as an Indonesian
citizen, I cannot free myself from my legal obligations. But every
one should know that this is a state based on law, and every
citizen is entitled to legal protections," Soeharto said Friday
when receiving A. Adirsyah from Majalah Dharmais, a magazine run
by one of the foundations previously chaired by Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto disclosed that he had 22 billion rupiah (3 million
U.S. dollars) deposited in three banks, not 72 billion rupiah as
the government had earlier claimed, and that his personal property
includes two houses in Jakarta and five hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
He said the money was saved from his salaries and pensions from
his time in the Armed Forces and his 32 years as president, as
well as his official travel allowances, dollar-denominated rentals
of two houses in Jakarta plus the interest earned on these bank
deposits.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto reiterated that he has no money stashed overseas.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was forced to step down on May 21 amid the country's
worst political and economic crisis in decades. He is accused of
corruption and abuse of power during his 32 years in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
