<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Beef up Drug Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- World football's governing body
FIFA admitted Friday there is a growing drug problem in soccer
and agreed in principle to introduce random tests.
</P>
<P>
But the executive committee continued to defy attempts by the
International Olympic Committee to harmonise doping sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Michel D'Hooghe, chairman of FIFA's committee for sports
medicine, told the meeting in Zurich of his serious concern about
a growing trend for drug abuse in football.
</P>
<P>
Italian soccer, in particular, has been rocked by doping
controversies this year. Magistrates launched an investigation
into alleged widespread doping in Serie A after allegations by
Roma coach Zdenek Zeman.
</P>
<P>
The committee backed D'Hooghe's call for random
out-of-competition testing but didn't decide when or how. "It's
going to have to be done together with the national
associations," said FIFA president Sepp Blatter.
</P>
<P>
FIFA again expressed reservations about the IOC's proposal for
minimum two-year suspensions for athletes found guilty of using
steroids or other serious drugs, with a life ban for a second
offence.
</P>
<P>
FIFA instead called for "flexibility regarding sanctions for
doping offenders."
</P>
<P>
FIFA was one of three federations - the others were those
representing tennis and cycling - which dissented on the
anti-doping resolutions adopted last Friday at a meeting of the
IOC and 35 Olympic sports bodies.
</P>
<P>
It objected to the two-year sanction on grounds that the
penalty might not stand up in court, and because certain
prohibited drugs have no performance-enhancing benefits in sports
like soccer.
</P>
<P>
But it has now said a panel of experts should be appointed to
keep up to date with rapid developments in the pharmaceutical
industry, and Blatter said FIFA's list of banned substances would
need to be updated monthly to keep up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
