<DOCNO> XIE19981205.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turner Sports Want to Stage Winter Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The first Winter Goodwill
Games is likely to be staged on 2000, U.S. Turner Sports
president Harvey Schiller said today.
</P>
<P>
Four summer Goodwill Games have been held, the winter edition
of the international sports event will be the first version of
the Olympic styled festival. It is mostly likely to be hosted in
Lake Placid, New York.
</P>
<P>
"There probably will be some extreme events included,"
Schiller said. "Maybe some of the bobsled or luge teams will go
down the track backwards."
</P>
<P>
The Goodwill schedule is likely to inclue events such like ice
climbing, snow bicycling and super-modified shovel racing. These
are not Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
Other sports on the program include alpine skiing, figure
skating, speedskating, bobsled, luge and at least one
cross-country ski event, according to Schiller.
</P>
<P>
Schiller said the Games probably would last 6-7 days. Lake
Placid, host city of Winter Olympics in 1932 and 1980, was the
probable site.
</P>
<P>
Schiller said the final decision would be made soon.
</P>
<P>
The Goodwill Games were the brainchild of Ted Turner, first
held in Moscow in 1986 after two straight Olympic boycotts.
</P>
<P>
The Goodwill Games lost millions of dollars for Turner and
parent company Time Warner, but drew respectable cable TV
audiences last summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
