<HEADLINE> FIFA Opens Door to 2002 World Cup Games in DPR Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- If South Korea wants to stage
some of its 2002 World Cup matches in the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea, FIFA would support the plan, world soccer's
governing body said in Zurich on Friday.
</P>
<P>
While FIFA statutes do not allow a third party to participate
in the World Cup finals, which will be co-hosted by South Korea
and Japan in 2002, the FIFA executive voted on Friday to support
the idea of some games being played in the DPR Korea, if South
Korea asks and if DPR Korea wants to be part of the competition.
</P>
<P>
"We do not initiate but we are open to dialogue if the
political climate facilitates that," said Blatter, who plans to
visit DPR Korea next autumn.
</P>
<P>
The executive committee also continued to discuss rescheduling
the 2002 World Cup to avoid the Asian rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said that after investigation he believes it is
possible to squeeze all 64 matches into the month of June,
starting the competition on the first and concluding on the 30th.
</P>
<P>
Blatter also confirmed that the controversial Confederations
Cup would begin in late July.
</P>
<P>
Dates for the first edition of a new World Club championship,
involving eight teams, was provisionally set for a nine day
period in January 2000 but will be co-ordinated with the
international competition calendar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
