<HEADLINE> Republican Governors Stress Tax Cuts, Other Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The impeachment debate
against President Bill Clinton is no excuse for paralysis on
issues such as tax cuts and better schools, say Republican
governors.
</P>
<P>
Seven Republicans governors met privately Friday with House
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston, and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, to discuss promotion of the Republican message on four
principles: lower taxes, improved public schools, better health
care and Social Security's future solvency, according to news
reports.
</P>
<P>
But the governors said afterwards that if the congressional
impeachment inquiry into the president's conduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair drags on into next year, that message will have a
difficult time breaking through.
</P>
<P>
Oklahoma Governor Frank Keating, chairman of the Republican
Governors Association, said it is in the national interest for
Congress to shift attention quickly to issues that affect
Americans more directly than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
"This process should not be an excuse for paralysis," Keating
told reporters. "Let's resolve the facts and move on."
</P>
<P>
The governors are pushing for a greater role in setting the
national Republican agenda. Sixteen Republican governors were
re-elected last month, for a total of 31, and they preside over 70
percent of the nation's population.
</P>
<P>
In a brief interview, Livingston said Republican congressional
leaders would consult more closely with their party's state chief
executives.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking for common ground where they can help us and we
can help them," the incoming speaker said.
</P>
<P>
Keating said these governors would lead task forces on issues:
Virginia's Jim Gilmore, taxes; Tennessee's Don Sundquist, health
care; Ridge, education; and Rowland, tobacco. Others will be named
later. 
</P>
