<HEADLINE> White House Voices Concern at Rush to Impeachment Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The White House said Friday
it was alarmed that House Republicans were pressing for an
impeachment vote against President Bill Clinton based more on
politics than constitutional seriousness.
</P>
<P>
"This isn't something that can be pushed off and dealt with in
a political way," said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark a day after House Majority Whip Tom Delay
reported that a vast majority of House Republicans are now
committed to a floor vote on articles of impeachment, and will not
entertain until later, if at all, a resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the White House was "willing to listen to any
proposals" relating to a censure, or reprimand, of Clinton. Some
members of Congress have proposed combining a censure of Clinton
with a requirement that he pay a fine. Clinton would have to agree
to pay any fine.
</P>
<P>
"This is an issue for members of Congress to discuss among
themselves and we will listen to any ideas that they want to put
forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is perhaps the most serious thing Congress can do. This
isn't a process where the House of Representatives can throw it to
the Senate to let them deal with it," Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said there has been a "serious lack of the constitutional
solemnity" that House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde had
promised.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the committee's sudden decision to include
controversies about Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign into its
deliberations this week, then drop them again, showed Republicans
have been "chaotic and erratic and politically motivated" and
failed to meet the high standard Hyde set out for his committee.
</P>
<P>
Incoming House Speaker Bob Livingston said the full House would
vote the week of December 14. He said a "vote this year would be
acceptable" if it is done in a fair way.
</P>
<P>
As the committee prepares to open its debate next week,
Clinton's attorneys planned to contact the committee Friday while
preparing to offer a defense of the president Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The committee gave the White House a Friday night deadline for
naming its potential witnesses for next week, but said a final
decision on allowing them would rest with panel members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
