<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End With Mixed Mode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets ended
with mixed mode Friday after a Wall Street rally of more than one
percent inspired European bourses to recoup their worst losses.
</P>
<P>
a strong Wall Street opening had helped European bourses to
move into positive territory in the wake of stronger-than-expected
U.S. employment data.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 index closed higher for the second straight
session, finishing up 15.8 points at 5,581.9, which was down 262.3
from a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Germany's blue-chip Xetra DAX index ended down 9.58 or 0.2
percent at 4,802.76 points, down 356.45 on the week. The Floor DAX
fell 11.85 or 0.25 percent to 4,775.23.
</P>
<P>
The French blue-chip CAC 40 closed 22.92 points higher at
3,738.59 in volume of 11.5 billion francs. The index was down
212.35 on the week.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the mood on the stock markets was also bolstered
by statements from German central bank President Hans Tietmeyer
that the U.S. and European economies remained robust and there was
little risk of an outbreak of a world financial crisis. 
</P>
