<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghali on New Role of Francophony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Francophony that had had
solely a cultural dimension acquired also political and economic
ones, said Francophony Secretary-General Boutros-Boutros Ghali
late Friday at his meeting with Romanian Prime Minister Radu
Vasile.
</P>
<P>
The former U.N. secretary-general was now in Bucharest to attend
the 12th session of the Francophony's Ministerial Conference.
</P>
<P>
Ghali pointed out the importance of the ongoing Francophony
Ministerial Conference, stressing that the Francophony that had
had solely a cultural dimension acquired also a political one.
</P>
<P>
He said it was open to cooperation with other world or regional
organizations, to the benefit of peace and democracy in
international relations.
</P>
<P>
"The Francophony also has an economic dimension which, despite
the fact that it does not have specific institutionalized
instruments, promotes a spirit of solidarity between its members,"
Ghali said, adding that a conference on investment and
international trade would be held next year in Monaco by the
economy and finance ministers of the member countries.
</P>
<P>
Radu Vasile saluted the new role the Francophony considered it
had to promote in international relations. He added that Romania
was interested in the development and institutionalization of the
Francophony economic dimension, while many countries in the
region, members of the organization, were in a stage of economic
transition.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Francophony Ministerial Conference opened its 12th
session in Bucharest, with the participation of the personal
representatives of heads of state or government in the 52 member
states of the French-speaking world. It is the first opportunity
for Romania to host such a gathering since it received full
membership of the movement in Mauritius in 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to Ghali, the session would debate "the main economic
and technical policies" of this international organization,
prepare the conference of the economic and finance ministers (due
in Monaco, April 14-15, 1999), the conference in Geneva (due on
March 20, 1999), and the 8th Francophony Summit (September 1999,
Moncton, Canada). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
