<HEADLINE> UK Insists Libyans Serve Jail in Scotland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom insisted on
Friday that the two Libyans who are accused of the 1988 Lockerbie
bombing must serve their jail terms in Scotland if they are
convicted.
</P>
<P>
"The key point on which we are insisting is that, if convicted,
the suspects would have to serve sentences in a Scottish prison,"
A Foreign Office spokesman said after Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
had a 15-minute telephone talks with The United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
"If they wished, Libyans could even station diplomats in
Scotland with unrestricted access to the prisoners," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Cook agreed to stay in constant touch over the
weekend when Annan flies to Tripoli for talks with Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi, said the the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Britain promised Libya unrestricted consular
access to the suspects if they were jailed in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 for its refusal
to hand over the two suspects who are accused by the United States
and Britain of blowing up a Pan-Am airliner over the Scottish town
of Lockerbie in December 1988, killing 270 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
