<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. stocks rebounded Friday
after a 184 point fall in the Dow Jones industrial average
Thursday with the blue-chip index closing 136.46 points higher to
9,016.14, according to preliminary data.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Labor Department reported Friday that the country's
unemployment rate fell to 4.4 percent in November, the lowest rate
since April and May which saw unemployment fall to a 28-year low
of 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The news boosted the market up as it spelt for the nation's
economic resiliency. Technology and financial shares led gains.
</P>
<P>
The week saw profit taking in Wall Street for the first four
sessions with two major declines Monday and Thursday. With
Friday's surge, the Dow is still 358 points from its peak of
9,374.27 on November 23.
</P>
<P>
Broader market indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 26.32 to 1,176.46 and the technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index was up 48.45 to 2,003.16.
</P>
<P>
On the New York Stock Exchange, advancers led decliners 2-1
with trading volume totaling 706 million shares, down from 797
million previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
