<HEADLINE> France Says Momentum in Seeking End to DRCongo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said on Friday that despite a delay of a peace meeting by
belligerent countries in the war of the Democratic Republic of
Congo has been postponed, the momentum in seeking an end to the
conflict is not over.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that the elan given in Paris should be lost like
this. One should simply expect errors, delays, complications, like
everywhere where one tries to make peace," he said in a television
interview.
</P>
<P>
He said that he believes all the countries involved in the
conflict are now tired and want a ceasefire, although an in-depth
solution is more difficult to make.
</P>
<P>
A meeting to be joined by countries involved in the DRCongo
conflict formerly scheduled for next Tuesday in Lusaka, Zambia,
has been postponed until December 14 because of unexplained
reasons.
</P>
<P>
The seven countries involved in the conflict -- DRCongo,
Uganda, Rwanda, Zimbabwe, Angola, Chad and Namibia -- agreed last
week in Paris to stop acts of hostilities immediately and sign a
ceasefire agreement by mid-December.  
</P>
</TEXT>
